<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Salmon farmers pour oil on
troubled water / A look at an environmental controversy in Chile's Lake
District
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN a group of angry Mapuche Indians and hotel owners attacked a truck in
the idyllic surroundings of Chile's Lake District last winter it was time
for salmon farmers to take stock of the effects of the unbridled expansion
of their business.
Chile's salmon exports have been doubling every year since commercial
production started in 1984. Last year 18,000 tonnes of the fish was flown
abroad, netting almost Dollars 100m. The salmon business is one of the
success stories of Chile's efforts to diversify exports away from copper,
but that success has at times run roughshod over the sensitivities of local
inhabitants.
Southern Chile is ideal for salmon farming. The eggs are hatched in the
crystalline rivers that spring from the Andes, the young smolts grow in
unpolluted lakes and the salmon mature in the relatively warm waters of the
south Pacific.
But the people of the Lake District fear their budding tourist industry
might be endangered if the lakes become contaminated by intensive fish
farming techniques.
Last year a colony of Mapuche Indians living on an island in the huge and
breathtaking Lake Ranco began to complain that the water was no longer safe
to drink. Hotel owners around the lake noticed a brown slime on beaches
close to where salmon cages had been installed.
Their alarm grew on learning that one salmon farming company planned to
increase the number of cages on Lake Ranco from 30 to 180. When appeals to
the authorities failed the locals took the law into their own hands, setting
up roadblocks to prevent feed trucks from reaching the salmon cages.
After two drivers were attacked last August a truce of a kind was declared.
Eicosal, the Arab-owned company at the centre of the dispute, agreed to
scale down its expansion to 50 cages. It also asked university scientists to
investigate the impact on the lake of their salmon cages and the
high-protein fishmeal used as nutrient.
The study showed that phosphate levels in Lake Ranco had increased
four-fold, but that the young smolts were not its primary cause. The main
polluting agents appeared to be the fertilisers that drained into the lake
from the pastures of nearby dairy farms.
Mr Eduardo Espinoza, the mayor of Lake Ranco, accepted the findings of the
report. 'But the problem is only half solved. He would like measurements to
be taken regularly, over a longer period. 'Lake Ranco is one of the purest
lakes in Chile. If we allow it to deteriorate we will also be destroying our
livelihood.'
Mr Espinoza says part of the ill feeling towards the salmon farmers was
caused by ignorance of this new activity and poor communication. This is
gradually being redressed.
Salmon farmers argue that it is in their best interests to keep the lakes
clean. Mr Pablo Achurra, director of operations of Marine Harvest
International, says: 'If the lakes became polluted, the young salmon would
be the first fish to die.' He says the Chilean authorities have imposed far
more stringent environmental standards on the salmon business than on dairy
farmers.
Marine Harvest International, a Scottish subsidiary of Unilever, has
invested Dollars 25m since it launched its Chilean operation in 1987. It
runs two hatcheries, four lake sites and 12 sea-water sites, which last year
produced 4,700 tonnes of salmon - more than three times the catch in 1989.
Mr Achurra says Marine Harvest and other companies have decided to put a
brake on this frenzied expansion. Overproduction in other countries,
particularly Norway, which is facing dumping charges in the US, have led
Chileans to reasses their marketing strategy.
Mr Achurra says: 'We no longer want to grow at exponential rates. We now
have to consolidate the industry, refine our techniques and aim for
consistent high quality.'
The success of intensive salmon farming has brought a fall in prices. Five
years ago a kilogram of salmon was fetching Dollars 10 in the US and Japan.
Last year prices hovered around Dollars 5.50.
Mr Rodrigo Infante, markettion of Chilean Salmon Exporters, believes this
will lead to a shake-out in the industry. The high profit margins attracted
a lot of cowboys to the business, but it is really an activity which favours
big companies with access to the latest technology and the benefits of
economies of scale.
The association forecasts exports will grow 11 per cent this year to 20,000
tonnes in spite of lower prices. Profit margins are narrower, but they are
not about to wipe out the business.
Chilean salmon has three advantages over its competitors in Canada, Scotland
and Norway. It supplies the US and Japan in winter, when fresh salmon is out
of season in the northern hemisphere, Chilean salmon grows faster and to
bigger sizes than its northern brethren, and its deep pink flesh is
particularly prized in Japan.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
