<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: History lesson spreads
optimism / A look at the pattern of US bond yields in recessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Economists and bond market analysts feel that the current US recession is
different from other post-war economic downturns.
'The months preceding the typical post-war recession are characterised by
rising core inflation, rising interest rates and rising levels of
inventories relative to sales,' said Mr Gerald Corrigan, chairman of the US
Federal Reserve bank in the bank's annual report.
'None of those conditions prevailed in any significant way in the months
preceding the downturn in economic activity last year. The roots of this
recession can be traced more directly to a combination of events that
precipitated a sharp decline in confidence and corresponding pull back in
spending.'
Against this background, measures of investor confidence take on extra
significance. Equity prices provide a broad measure of anticipated growth in
corporate earnings. A more sensitive gauge may be provided by corporate
yield spreads (the extra yield on corporate bonds against government bonds)
and credit spreads (the extra yield of bonds issued by weak companies
against those issued by strong companies).
When the economic outlook is bleak, corporate yield spreads against
government bonds widen in anticipation of deteriorating credit quality. A
recovery is prefaced by a tightening of spreads.
Moreover, by looking at the yield spread between company bond issues of
different credit quality, investors' perception of the risk to various areas
of the economy can be judged.
JP Morgan, the US securities house, calculates a number of industrial bond
yield indices in the US market according to the credit quality of the
issuer. These show that yield spreads and credit spreads have already
peaked.
'Credit spreads usually start widening after the onset of a recession and
reach a peak just before or after the end of a recession, at which point
economic activity has reached a trough,' said Mr Jan Loeys, bond market
analyst at JP Morgan.
The yield spread between top-rated triple-A corporate bond issues and
medium-grade Baa rated bond issues peaked at 192 basis points in December
last year. The spread between the two credit grades has since steadily
narrowed to 151 basis points.
This compares favourably with the recession of the early 1980s, when the
credit spread soared to 293 basis points as investors ran to the best
quality bond issues.
In contrast, the current downturn in confidence looks more serious than the
recession of the early 1970s. In 1974 the yield spread between top-rated and
weaker corporate bonds hit a peak of just 154 basis points, 40 basis points
less than the 1990-91 peak.
Weaker companies are seen to be more at risk than strong companies this time
around. One explanation is that the financial system is no longer seen as a
willing supplier of emergency credit to stretched industrial companies.
'This recession was different to the early 1980s or mid-1970s. Fears of a
credit crunch and the high degree of leverage among US corporations were new
factors, over and above depressed demand,' said Mr Loeys.
Yet for top-rated triple-A companies, the yield spread over government bonds
widened to a peak of just 70 basis points against 197 basis points in 1974.
For those companies in good financial health, with low gearing and strong
cash flow, the current recession is seen as a less serious threat than in
the early 1970s.
There are pitfalls in taking this analysis too far. For example, the
credit-rating agencies were aggressive in their downgrading of companies
coming into this recession, so the data may not be strictly comparable.
However, the tightening of yield spreads and credit spreads, during the last
two months in particular, suggests a definite upswing in investor
confidence.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
