<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Company News: Air NZ chief executive resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JIM Scott, Air New Zealand's chief executive, has resigned, apparently
over differences with the airline's controlling shareholder, Brierley
Investments, which is believed to be strengthening its control.
This follows the announcement that Mr Bob Matthew, former BIL New Zealand
chief executive, has stepped down to concentrate his energies on the
airline, the position widely seen as making him the airline's executive
chairman.
At the same time, several key Air New Zealand appointments have been filled
by the former executives of another BIL subsidiary, Magnum Corporation, a
company formerly run by Mr Matthew.
There were also differences in style and personality between Mr Scott and
BIL executives. Mr Scott wanted to concentrate on strategic long-term growth
for the company and New Zealand tourism: BIL seemed more concerned with
improving retail earnings. On several occasions statements from Mr Scott on
such areas as manning and expansion, appeared to clash with those of Mr
Matthew.
Mr Scott's background was as a senior executive and specialist in forestry
with Carter Holt. He is being replaced in an acting capacity by the deputy
chief executive, Mr Jim McCrea, a long-serving employee who has considerable
standing with BIL executives for his skill at negotiating the purchase of
new aircraft at favourable rates.
A statement from Mr Matthew said he accepted Mr Scott's resignation with
regret, saying he had played a leading role in the changes since the airline
was privatised.
</TEXT>
