<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Company News: Fuji Heavy to miss dividend
payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FUJI Heavy Industries, the maker of Subaru cars, said yesterday that
dividend payments would be passed for the year to end-March, as the company
would incur an after-tax loss of Y66.4bn (Dollars 4.82m).
The company reported an after-tax profit of Y5.7bn for the previous year,
but had offset an operating loss with sales of securities holdings. The
stock market plunge last year had restricted the com-pany's ability to sell
further shares, and the previous dividend of Y6 will not be repeated.
Fuji Heavy has close ties to Nissan Motor, which owns 4.2 per cent of the
company and has indicated it could take a more active role in management.
Nissan has consigned production of one of its models to Fuji Heavy from
October of this year.
Officials at Fuji Heavy said yesterday that the company had suffered an
after-tax loss of Y51.3bn in the first half and a Y15.1bn loss in the second
half, despite strong consumer demand last year.
Total output for the Japanese industry in the year to end-March rose 4.9 per
cent, while Fuji's output rose 7.3 per cent and its domestic sales, by
volume, rose 14.8 per cent.
However, the domestic car market has turned down in recent months and
Japanese makers are also reporting slower sales in the US and Europe,
complicating Fuji Heavy's plans to break even this year.
</TEXT>
