<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Company News: Multi-Purpose announces 46%
decline in turnover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIM SIONG HOON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MULTI-PURPOSE, the diversified Malaysian group, unveiled a 46 per cent drop
in turnover to MDollars 279m (USDollars 101.4m) last year, reflecting the
extent it has shrunk from its previous status as one of the country's
largest conglomerates.
Its profit margin rose, however, from 1.5 per cent to 10 per cent to help
raise pre-tax profit from MDollars 30m in 1989 to MDollars 52m, the best it
achieved in more than a decade of its troubled and heavily borrowed life.
After-tax profit and minority interests stood at MDollars 26m, or 3.5
Malaysian cents in earnings per share, compared with 0.8 cents previously.
Over the past year, the group, under Mr Lim Thian Kiat, chief executive, has
shrunk from six divisions to four; banking, shipping, property and lottery.
The rationalisation - which produced MDollars 110m in net extraordinary gain
and MDollars 136m in attributable profit last year - still leaves shipping
yet to be sold, after the trading and engineering and plantation divisions.
Multi-Purpose's lottery operation remains its biggest earner, with after-tax
profit doubling to nearly MDollars 34m. This is followed by banking and
property.
The group plans to use the proceeds from last year's sales, in particularly
MDollars 478m from its plantations, to lift its Dunlop Estate stake in the
Magnum lottery, leisure and finance group from 40 to 100 per cent.
Last March, Dunlop raised MDollars 310m, MDollars 260m of it in 10 per cent,
five-year loan stocks, to acquire 30 per cent in Magnum from a friendly
party. But Arab-Malaysian Merchant Bank has urged minority shareholders to
reject the rest of the offer, at MDollars 7.42 a share, compared with more
than MDollars 10 being traded.
Reconstruction at Magnum and Dunlop is in the pipeline, by consolidating its
lottery operations under a new listed group and expanding its finance
operations through the acquisition of a stockbroker.
</TEXT>
