<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / International Company News: Japanese to lift stake in
Brazilian steel mill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN obstacle hindering Brazil's first significant privatisation - that of
Usiminas, its largest steel mill - was removed yesterday with the signing of
an accord substantially raising the equity of the company's Japanese
shareholders.
After months of negotiations it was agreed that Nippon Usiminas, a Nippon
Steel-led consortium of 54 Japanese companies as well as the Japanese
government, would have its stake in Usiminas increased from 4.6 per cent to
13 per cent.
The agreement resolves years of complaints by the Japanese over the
systematic reduction of their equity which, as a result of government
accounting practices, was reduced from 25 per cent.
Usiminas was established in 1958 as a joint Brazilian-Japanese venture to
provide steel for the motor and naval industries. The Japanese put up 52 per
cent of the capital and retained 40 per cent of the equity, the maximum a
foreign company could hold.
Nippon Steel provided the latest equipment and technical assistance making
the mill the most efficient in Brazil. But government price controls on
steel to subsidise other industries, and more recently to keep down
inflation, prevented it becoming the profitable venture envisaged. So, as
Brazil increased investment in Usiminas, the Japanese cut their
participation to hold only 25 per cent of the equity.
The real blow came in 1976 when all state steel companies were brought under
the control of Siderbras which, through redirecting tax reimbursements,
drastically reduced the equity participation of Nippon Usiminas from 25 per
cent to 4.6 per cent.
The story of Usiminas is seen as highlighting the problems Japanese
investors have had in Brazil. 'This is Japan's saddest experience in
Brazil,' said Mr Toshiro Kobayashi, president of the Council of the Bank of
Tokyo and also head of the committee to promote Brazilian-Japanese
relations.
'Not only was Japanese equity slashed, but because of government
intervention in the steel sector Japanese investors have never received a
dividend.'
Consequently when Usiminas was placed top of the Collor government's targets
for privatisation the Japanese threatened to block it unless their equity
was increased.
Yesterday's accord to raise their share to 13 per cent means the
privatisation is expected to proceed in July. There is unlikely to be any
Japanese interest.
Mr Hiroyuki Nakagawa, president of Nippon Steel in Brazil, said, 'With price
controls active I can't see any Japanese buyers. We have enjoyed nothing
from our investment in Usiminas.' Last year Usiminas made a real loss
despite a declared profit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
