<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Acas sees strikes at record low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A RECORD low in the number of strikes last year was matched by the highest
level of individual claims to the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration
Service (Acas), the service said yesterday in its annual report.
The number of officially recorded strikes fell to a 55-year low in 1990. At
the same time, the number of individual conciliation claims that statutory
employment rights had been infringed was the highest since Acas was
established in 1975, the report stated.
The chairman of Acas, Mr Douglas Smith, said the low level of strikes
reflected a 'shift in the balance of power'. Unions had lost one in four of
their members over the past 10 years and were finding it difficult to
recruit among such groups as part-time workers and financial services
employees. Trade unions were also much more pragmatic about what needed to
be accepted in order to preserve jobs, he added.
Complaints alleging sex and race discrimination in employment were the
highest ever; formal complaints of unfair dismissal rose by almost a quarter
over 1989; and allegations of unlawful deductions from pay rose by about 50
per cent. Overall, there were more than 52,000 individual cases for
conciliation, the report stated. Requests for collective arbitration in
industrial disputes rose by 8 per cent to about 1,300.
Individuals were increasingly prepared to pursue their rights under the law,
said Mr Smith. In addition, the 'shake-out of labour' resulting from the
recession had increased all Acas's activities, he said.
The number of complaints relating to the implementation of redundancies
almost doubled during the year. These complaints often involved the methods
of selection for redundancy, according to the report.
An increasing number of organisations had sought to move away from
long-standing 'last in, first out' agreements in favour of other
arrangements which they considered offered the best path to a skilled and
balanced workforce, Acas said.
While unions still sought to match pay claims to inflation, it was
increasingly employers' views about what they could afford to pay that were
determining pay increases, said the report.
'It was notable, in particular, that where employers had been open and frank
about difficult trading circumstances and what might be needed to preserve
jobs, lower settlements proved possible,' Acas concluded.
</TEXT>
