<TEXT>
Sir, Your leader 'Listening to employees' (April 23), cites the Involvement
and Participation Association/Institute of Personnel Management code of
practice on employee involvement and says Mr Michael Howard, the employment
secretary, 'should consider endorsing it'. This association welcomes Mr
Howard's initiative, but you should be aware that the code was endorsed by
the then employment secretary, Tom King, at the time of its publication in
1983.
We feel that something more than endorsement is needed and would like to see
the code underpinned by statute. This would set clear minimum standards for
employee involvement. Such a development would be infinitely preferable to
the present Brussels proposals on employee involvement, would cause no
problem to those companies which have already made progress in this
direction, and could have a real impact on improving employee involvement.
We are currently collecting examples of where employee involvement has made
a direct impact on business performance.
BC Stevens,
director,
