<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Letter: No quick route to creating a free market economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JIM EGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Implicit in Stanley Katz's excellent article ('East Europe should learn
from Asia', April 24) are also some lessons for the west with respect to the
regeneration of the former command economies.
First, despite the reservations that many would share about Mr Katz's
specific suggestions, there should be a wider acceptance of the fact that
western nations are no more experienced at building market economies in a
matter of weeks and months than anyone else. While the theoretical appeal of
an overnight metamorphosis is great, the (as yet still unknown) costs in
terms of jobs and livelihoods seem frequently to be dismissed rather
lightly.
Of course, the transition will inevitably involve high costs but, given the
fragile nature of the new democracies, failure to account correctly for the
crucially important public support for reform risks the failure of the
reform process itself. The exercise continues to be an experiment where
there is no place for narrow minds and capitalist dogmatism at the expense
of political and social sensitivity.
Moreover, to say we live in free market economies is to make a claim that
must be riddled with caveats. It is rather sanctimonious to insist that the
eastern Europeans should embrace the market while the west is often
reluctant to do the same. For example it is clear that the question of
property rights is central to the reform process and that the case for
privatisation is extremely strong.
However it could be argued that the British can hardly afford to preach
about privatisation on the basis of its recent experience, which boasts the
conversion of public monopolies to private ones and the legally enforced
protection of utilities from competition as its main features.
The temptation must be avoided smugly to assume that the west has all the
answers. There are far too many opportunities and aspirations at stake.
Jim Egan,
31 Kidbrooke Grove,
Blackheath,
London SE3 OLE
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2271</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLABKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Foreign Affairs: Europe's teetering pillar - The French are
resisting Nato leaders' efforts to modify the continent's defence
arrangements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The French government, I discovered on a recent visit to Paris, is strongly
against building a 'European pillar' of Nato, and is determined to thwart
British efforts to use the Western European Union (WEU) for that purpose.
Although it has joined in discussions on the Nato strategy review, it does
not like the way these discussions are going and has no intention of joining
any integrated Nato command structure, still less any of the 'multinational
corps' promised by Nato leaders in their London Declaration last year.
For President Francois Mitterrand, it seems, only two things are important.
One is the Atlantic alliance, which he sees as the essential reality of
European security today. He believes it works well as it is. France's
performance in the Gulf war showed, according to French officials, that you
do not need to be part of the integrated command in peacetime to function as
a good ally in war.
France, they point out, has always accepted that, in a war with the Soviet
Union, the US would take command. Without that, in their view, there would
be no US nuclear guarantee - and therefore France is against the idea,
sometimes canvassed by Americans, of having a European as Supreme Allied
Commander Europe (Saceur).
But, they say, the only rationale for having an integrated command in
peacetime was to enable Nato to respond quasi-automatically to a surprise
attack. The proposal for multinational corps tends to reinforce this
'automaticity' at the very time when the diminution of Soviet conventional
forces, and their withdrawal from eastern Europe, are making a surprise
attack impossible.
In future crises, the French argue, there will be time for political
consultation, and it will be absolutely necessary. As an example, they cite
the German experience in January, when German aircraft were called on, as
part of the joint mobile force permanently assigned to Allied Command
Europe, to defend Turkey against possible Iraqi retaliation for US attacks
from Turkish bases, about which Germany had not been consulted. France does
not want its political options to be foreclosed in this way by the
'automatic' involvement of its forces.
So France's ideal alliance, in theory, would be one with no integrated
military command in peacetime. Nato's military committee (composed of
national chiefs-of-staff) would 'resume its preponderant place', with the
task of proposing military solutions to the North Atlantic Council. The
military command would be adapted to the particular solution chosen in any
given crisis.
This arrangement would give all Nato members the same freedom of action that
France now enjoys. Whether the French would really welcome it, one may
doubt. Had the US, Britain and others not been used to working together in
Nato - indeed, had France not been used to liaising with Nato command for
practical purposes - the allied performance in the Gulf might have been very
different. However, the French know their suggestions are in no danger of
being accepted, and they insist that France is not demanding anything: if
others want to reinforce the integrated command that is their affair. France
is quite happy with the alliance as it is.
The other thing Mr Mitterrand cares about is, of course, Europe: the future
European Union. He accepts that this cannot be implemented today, but
insists that when finished it must have competence in defence as well as
foreign and security policy. France wants this written into the treaty on
European political union, since to leave it out would imply 'a Europe of
limited sovereignty'.
If WEU can be gradually developed into the defence arm of the European
Union, well and good. But the French will not accept it as a 'pillar' of
Nato, nor yet as a 'bridge' between Nato and the EC. 'To build a bridge you
need two banks,' they say, 'and the European bank does not yet exist.' The
Dutch and British are accused of wanting to 'absorb Europe into Nato'. But
the main argument is seen as being between France and Britain. The French
are confident that the Germans, Italians, Spanish and Belgians are all on
side; they consider that Portugal will go along with whatever Britain
decides; and they speak with scorn of the Dutch desire to have things all
ways at once: pacifism, a supranational Europe, and defence run by the US.
On one point, at least, France and Britain are agreed: foreign and security
policy is too important to be handed over to supranational institutions.
These aspects of European Union will be kept firmly inter-governmental, much
to the disgust of Mr Jacques Delors.
As might be expected, the French bristle with indignation at the round robin
sent to European governments in February by Mr Reginald Bartholomew, a
senior US state department official, warning Europe not to set up any kind
of caucus which might pre-empt Nato decisions. In general, the French reject
as 'childish blackmail' any argument that Europeans should abstain from a
given course of action in order not to isolate or alienate the Americans.
They stick to the old Gaullist view on this point: the US is in Europe for
its own interests, not out of sentiment. Any conceivable US president will
want to keep it there, and Europeans should not be taken in by any threats.
Yet in the same breath they say that Europe must eventually be ready to
assume its own defence, because it would be unwise to count on the Americans
being here for ever.
This contradiction is reconciled by reference to the US Congress, which in
French eyes seems to be a mysterious, elemental force, unpredictable and
quite unamenable to European influence. Here, no doubt, lies the key to
Franco-British differences. The British see, or think they see, the US from
inside, and believe their actions can have some effect on its political
processes. The French think, or pretend to think, that this is quite
pointless, and that Europe should be prepared for the worst even while
hoping for the best.
Ironically enough this attitude brings the French very close to the US
position on the substance of the immediate point at issue: they don't want
any 'European caucus' within Nato either. Senior military figures in France
are even sceptical about the idea, fashionable in some European circles, of
a WEU 'rapid reaction force' for use outside the Nato area. Talk of 'double
hatting' this force, to make it available also for use by Nato in an
appropriate context, arouses French suspicions that it is yet another
British wheeze to inveigle them back into the Nato structure.
From all this I deduce that the prospects for any concrete manifestation of
Europe's much-touted 'defence identity' are less good than they looked a
month or two ago. While Britain and Holland drag their feet for fear of
upsetting the Americans, the French will drag theirs for fear of setting up
something which would reinforce American hegemony. Probably Britain will
compromise to the extent of allowing some vague phrase in the treaty on
European political union to the effect that defence is not excluded, on the
understanding that nothing will actually be done. Meanwhile Nato will
restructure itself in some diminished and rather undramatic form; the WEU
will confine itself to co-ordinating marginal European contributions to
American-led operations outside Europe; and nothing much will happen until
the next crisis.
But of course that could be tomorrow.
</TEXT>
