</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Arts: Flog it to them - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first joke-riddle many of us ever heard was probably asked by our
grandmothers: 'Do you know the difference between an elephant and a pillar
box?' No Granny. 'Then I shan't send you to post a letter'. For those who
work at ACBS (A Certain Building Society) this has now been superseded by
another question: do you know the difference between swimming with sharks
and swimming with dolphins? No? Then we shan't be doing any more business
with your company.
ACBS is responsible for the most irksomely pretentious television commercial
in living memory; that breathtakingly expensive bit of nonsense (modishly
shot in black and white, with the sort of inverted snobbery so
characteristic of the advertising business) in which a man with trendy
designer stubble and an oh-so-sincere voice (would you trust this poseur as
far as you could throw him? nor would I) reads out a letter to his son, full
of voguish green sentiments.
It is the most portentous claptrap imaginable: 'You have left your home to
seek your paradise, to find your truth, to walk softly in the footsteps of
older, wiser people, to swim with the sharks and the dolphins ..'
'Flog a mortgage company to a TV audience? Piece of cake old boy; shoot 'em
the green and caring line. They'll lap it up ..' Well, perhaps a few
credulous teenage greenies will, but they don't have much money to spend on
mortgages, and experience as a Gallup Poll interviewer suggests that most
ordinary people will not remember which particular company this commercial
is supposed to promote.
Lacking a memorable jingle, rhyme, or pack-shot to serve as a trade-name
mnemonic, a commercial can actually be counter-productive and help increase
the sales of your competitors. Research by an American brewer suggested that
their commercials with tempting shots of foaming glasses did prompt the
drinking of more beer - usually the viewer's favourite brand, whichever that
happened to be. The ACBS ad is so preoccupied with looking fashionable that
the business of ramming home the brand name is forgotten. Can you name the
company?
The admen, those chaps in designer stubble, granny glasses and recession
chic (suits that don't fit) have two standard responses to this sort of
criticism. First 'Say what you like, we've got you talking about our
commercial and that was the idea', and secondly 'Whatever you may say, the
more advertising a company does on television the more it sells, so it
works, you see'. The first argument is specious: over the years we have been
induced to talk plenty about Aids and mugging but that does not make us want
them. We can be well aware of the existence of something and wholly against
it.
The second argument is a classic example of the fallacy of the undistributed
middle. In primary schools the children with larger feet invariably have the
better handwriting, but only a fool concludes that the former causes the
latter: those with the larger feet happen to be older. Those that buy the
most advertising on television happen to be the bigger companies, but there
is no proof that the former causes the latter. Companies have achieved
enormous success and even brand leadership without buying any advertising
(Babe Ruth chocolate bars in the US, Sainsbury's in Britain).
So advertisers who are told by the stubble and granny specs brigade that it
doesn't matter if the public makes fun of your commercials, so long as they
notice them, might try murmuring to themselves 'You're never alone with a
Strand'. This notorious cigarette campaign attracted endless attention yet
killed the product stone dead. Everyone noticed it but no one wanted to
identify with a brand so favoured by the lonely.
Of course it takes all sorts to make a world, different viewers react in
different ways, and likes and dislikes among the commercials can arise from
little more than prejudice. My current bete noir - 'If yore sat arahnd at
'ome, Make new friends on the tell-er-foam' - no doubt seems like a godsend
to some people. There may be saintly viewers who, upon being told for the
17th time that everyone's after Bernard Maffews' crispy crumbly turkey
stools (or is it steaks?) do not scream at the television 'Oh no they're
not, I'm not'.
The likes are just as idiosyncratic. Who would have dreamed that the naughty
roller-skating pandas could continue to get laughs for Kit Kat after so many
months? Or that the Nazi hero and the squawking Lancaster navigator in
Carling's dam-buster spoof would go on and on seeming funny? As for Robbie
Coltrane and his granny in the Persil liquid ad, do they seem especially
welcome in their own right, or is it because we had all become so fed up
with those deadly Nanette Newman commercials? There is, surely, a serious
point behind all this. It must be better to be funny and create affection
than to be too clever by half and create fury or, equally counter
productive, bafflement.
On television at present there are a number of motor car campaigns which are
either baffling or off-putting or both. Would you really want to buy a car
that was so boring it sent you to sleep? That is what Rover's agency seems
to imagine: they show a chap taking a baby for a drive and before long both
of them are zizzing away.
According to Audi's agency theirs is the sort of car bought by people who
crash head-on into each other and climb out grinning inanely. Will this
persuade you to buy? And how about that other one which, until recently,
kept hurtling through the plate glass on the top floor of a factory? 'Built
by loonies for suicidal Scandinavians' seemed to be the message. Merely to
get noticed is not enough: you can hardly not notice the fact that Cadbury
and Ford are both currently using Dave Brubeck's 1961 hit 'Take Five', the
first to promote Twirl and the second to promote the Orion, but if you are
anything like me that will ensure that you never buy either.
Having a reputation for cleverness and wit, as British commercials do, is
all very well even if the people who pay the fees of the designer stubble
chaps might prefer a reputation for improved sales. For viewers, cleverness
and wit is far more entertaining than hard sell, but when it backfires -
when you lisp away huskily about swimming with the sharks - and irritate
viewers, the entire process has surely been turned on its head.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
