<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / FT Law Report: Swiss bank instructions are set aside
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL DAVIES, Barrister
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANK OF CRETE SA v KOSKOTAS AND OTHERS Court of Appeal (Lord Justice Parker,
Lord Justice Staughton and Sir David Croom-Johnson): March 14 1991
THE COURT has power to order a defendant to instruct his Swiss bank to
disclose account documents for the purpose of a contested application for
continuance of a Mareva injunction; but the order will be set aside if its
purpose disappears in that the defendant abandons his opposition to the
injunction, and if an application to stay or set aside the main action is
pending which, if successful, would make disclosure unnecessary.
The Court of Appeal so held when allowing an appeal by Mr Georgis Louvaris
and Brockton Investments Ltd, the ninth and 10th defendants in an action
against Mr George Koskotas, Mr Panayottis Vakalis and others, from Mr
Justice Mummery's decision ordering Mr Louvaris to instruct his Swiss bank
to disclose account documents for the purposes of a Mareva application by
the plaintiff, the Bank of Crete SA.
LORD JUSTICE STAUGHTON said that Mr Louvaris lived in Greece. Brockton was
said to be controlled by him.
The facts alleged in the action were that Mr Koskotas held an important
position in the Bank of Crete, and had misappropriated Dollars 200m from its
assets with the assistance of Mr Vakalis, who also held a position with the
bank. Some of that money was said to have come into the hands of Mr Louvaris
and Brockton.
Two particular sums were identified, of DM250,000 and DM650,000. Out of
those monies Brockton was said to have bought a flat in Finchley Road in St
John's Wood.
The Bank of Crete claimed to be able to trace the monies and to have a
charge on them, and similar remedies in respect of the flat.
On May 2 1990 Mr Justice Mummery ordered Mr Louvaris to sign a letter
instructing his Swiss bank, United Overseas Bank, to disclose his account
documents for the period January 1 1987 to October 31 1988. By the order, if
Mr Louvaris defaulted in signing he would be debarred from defending the
action.
Counsel were given an opportunity to agree the letter. It said: 'I hereby
instruct you to proceed and make single copies at my cost of each of the
foregoing documents.' It released the bank from any liability under Swiss
law and asked that the documents be sent to a firm of Swiss lawyers acting
for the Bank of Crete.
When the judge made that order there were other motions shortly to be heard
in the Chancery Division. One was a motion to continue a Mareva injunction
which had been granted ex parte over the English assets of Mr Louvaris and
Brockton.
There were also motions by Mr Louvaris and Brockton to set aside the
proceedings for want of jurisdiction, or to stay proceedings on the ground
that England was not the appropriate forum.
The reason Mr Justice Mummery made the somewhat unusual order was that there
had already been a contest as to whether the existing Mareva injunction
should be continued. Mr Louvaris and Brockton were saying they had been
guilty of no misappropriation and that there was no cause of action.
At an earlier stage Mr Justice Morritt had said there ought to be a measure
of discovery to enable the Bank of Crete to check the assertions in the
affidavits made on behalf of Mr Louvaris and Brockton. That was an unusual
measure. Normally a judge made up his mind on the affidavit evidence at that
stage.
After the original order for discovery a consent order was made, on February
7 1990, for production of documents relating to Mr Louvaris's D-Mark account
with the Swiss bank, and also relating to an item in his account described
as 'vente devises'.
At first the documents were not produced. Then documents relating to the
general account were produced with account numbers obliterated. There was a
protest and further copies were produced, again with account numbers
obliterated. Eventually proper copies were produced. Documents relating to
the 'vente devises' were not produced and the solicitors for Mr Louvaris and
Brockton, no doubt on instructions, said they did not exist. Eventually a
document relating to that transaction was produced.
So there was quite some history when the matter came before Mr Justice
Mummery.
Mr Louvaris now appealed against his order.
Mr Hollington for Mr Louvaris pointed out that on June 18 1990, while the
present appeal was pending, his instructing solicitors wrote to the Bank of
Crete's solicitors, saying they abandoned their opposition to the Mareva.
Eventually it was said that the abandonment applied to both Mr Louvaris and
Brockton.
Accordingly, Mr Hollington submitted, since Mr Justice Mummery's order had
been made for the purpose of the Mareva application, it was no longer
necessary. Mr Thomas for the Bank of Crete said the purpose of the order was
not solely to enable the bank to sustain its application for continuation of
the Mareva.
When one looked at the affidavit of the Bank of Crete's solicitor, it was
plain that the immediate purpose of the application to Mr Justice Mummery
was to enable the bank to sustain its application for a Mareva injunction.
At first sight it seemed there was no longer any need for Mr Justice
Mummery's order. It might be that at a later stage the ordered documents
might be relevant and discoverable in the action.
But the application by Mr Louvaris and Brockton to set aside or stay the
proceedings was due to be heard shortly after the May 2 proceedings. When
the appeal was lodged against the May 2 order, it was decided to adjourn the
application until the appeal had been disposed of.
In the result, an application to set aside or stay the proceedings was still
pending.
Mr Hollington submitted that the application had some chance of success. He
observed that Mr Louvaris lived in Greece. Little affecting him took place
in the UK, except perhaps for the purchase of the Finchley Road flat.
The application to set aside or stay the proceedings was not frivolous. If
it succeeded there would never be a substantive order for discovery of the
documents in the action against Mr Louvaris and Brockton. They were entitled
to have that application determined before there was a substantive order for
discovery. If it failed there could then, if necessary, be a renewed
application for discovery.
So, although the documents might prove relevant at a later stage, that was
not sufficient ground for upholding the judge's order now that opposition to
the Mareva injunction had been abandoned.
Mr Hollington's second point was that there was no power to order that a
party should send a letter to his bank and that if he defaulted he would be
debarred from defending.
The court was referred to Order 24 rule 16 of the Rules of the Supreme
Court.
Under Order 24 rule 16 the same effect could have been achieved by ordering
Mr Louvaris and Brockton to disclose the documents and, if they were in
their power, to obtain them from whoever had custody of them. If they failed
to comply, they could have been debarred from defending.
It was said the judge should not have made the order because there was only
a trivial interface between the dollar account of which disclosure was
sought and the D-Mark account which was relevant to the proceedings.
That was a matter for the judge's discretion in the light of the action's
history of discovery. He was entitled to take the view that the dollar
account ought to be disclosed.
It might be that the judge's order short-circuited the matter somewhat, but
it was not on that ground, in view of the history of the case, an order he
had no power to make.
It was said for Mr Louvaris that a Swiss bank would not comply with a
request in the form of the letter scheduled to the judge's order.
Evidence was produced from a Swiss lawyer to that effect. The Bank of Crete
produced evidence from another Swiss lawyer to the contrary effect. The
issue was not determined.
The Swiss were sensitive about their banking secrecy laws and also about
intrusion into their affairs by court order from other countries.
But even if the Swiss bank would not or might not comply with the request in
the letter, that by itself would not be a ground for the judge not to make
the order.
The order should not be interfered with on those other grounds. However, in
the events that had now happened it should be set aside. The appeal was
allowed.
Their Lordships agreed.
For the Bank of Crete: Neville Thomas QC and Ian Geering (Denton Hall Burgin
&amp; Warrens).
For Mr Louvaris: Robin Hollington (Zaiwalla &amp; Co).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2277</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEABLABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910501
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Jobs: Stress at work - a question of upbringing:
Vulnerability in face of pressure is often linked with experiences during
childhood
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WHAT'S a challenge to one person may be stress to a second, and a third's
breaking point.' Besides being perennially one of the truer maxims about
working life, that saying can rarely if ever have been of more urgent
relevance to so many people.
Recession added to sharpening trade rivalry create conditions suited only to
supreme optimists, who characteristically see every setback as short-term,
one-off and above all the fault of someone or something other than
themselves. Challenges to them tend to be anxieties to those of us who are
less sure of our own perfection, regarding failures as symptoms of personal
deficiency.
Nevertheless even habitually self-critical people's tendency to be stressed
by things others take nonchalantly is often not their own fault. I say that
on the evidence of research by the Leeds University psychologist Jenny
Firth-Cozens which, although focused mainly on junior hospital doctors, has
produced findings her other work suggests apply to executives too.
Her studies show that proneness to stress is linked with conditions of
upbringing. So it seems probable that by recognising such links, people
suffering from the liability can make themselves more robust.
For instance, readers who feel stress-prone may care to consider their
father's age at their birth. The research revealed an impressive contrast in
robustness between those respectively born to fathers under and over
approximately 35.
Among the junior doctors, all aged 22-23, those who never felt stressed had
fathers whose average age at the time of the study was 52. That compared
with 59 for the dads of the doctors who were 'cased' - the technical term
for people who, although still physically well, are distractingly worried.
Another factor apparently strongly linked with vulnerability was the
mother's death before the child was 15. On the other hand, divorce had only
a weak link and death of the father showed no association at all.
But in the particular case of executives, the Leeds psychologist believes
the main contributor to vulnerability is paternal rather than maternal
influence. Among managers she has studied, it was those with powerful and
critical fathers who most saw their bosses at work as sources of anxiety.
The explanation may be that, as Freud conjectured, they project their
father's stressful personality onto their chiefs, interpreting them as ogres
although they may in fact be considerate souls.
Even so, Jenny Firth-Cozens is well aware that bosses can be exceedingly
stressful in their own right. Witness her finding that, regardless of
personal vulnerability, the junior doctors in teaching hospitals - where top
consultants have traditionally treated their underlings in domineering style
 -were markedly more stressed than the juniors employed elsewhere.
That, she says, is noteworthy evidence that something in the management of
teaching hospitals is wrong. To the Jobs column's mind, it is also something
even hospital chiefs short of money ought to be able to put right.
NOW to the table alongside giving a sample of the results of Day Associates'
latest quarterly survey of pay and perks in some five dozen international
banks and investment houses in the City of London. Anyone who wants the full
report, which covers 191 types of staff, should contact Joe Clark at Suite
2.31, 75 Whitechapel Rd, London E1 1DU; tel 071-375 1397, fax 071-375 1723.
The price to concerns not taking part in the survey is Pounds 175 plus VAT.
My figures refer to a mere 15 fairly senior positions. First come base
salaries, the lower quartile representing the person a quarter way up from
the foot of a ranking of all in the same kind of work, the median the person
mid-way, and the upper quartile the one a quarter way down from the top.
Then we have the average salary, followed by the percentage of it typically
received as an additional bonus. Lastly come the percentage of the people in
each type of job who have a company car, and its average price.
HEADHUNTER Paul Chambers of the Freshman Consultancy seeks two recruits for
separate clients he may not name. So he promises to honour applicants'
requests not to be identified to the employer at this stage.
His first quarry is a head for the German sales operations of an American
financial information group. Although its Frankfurt office where the
newcomer will be based is small, it already has numerous established
customers.
The job is to take the lead in building up the German business, and
candidates should have a record of go-getting success in the financial
information market. They must also be fluent in German.
Salary indicator DM200,000-250,000. Car among other benefits.
The second post, London-based but again with a US group, is for a seller of
software for capital markets uses. Computer knowledge is not needed, but
candidates must have detailed understanding of capital markets trading
especially in off-balance-sheet instruments.
Salary plus bonus on results about Pounds 50,000. Perks include car.
Inquiries to 81-103 Euston St, London NW1 2ET; tel 071-388 3111, fax 071 388
3588.
