<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Management: Management abstracts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Accounting standards and the judiciary. G W Radcliffe in Accounting and
Business Research (UK), Autumn 90 (8 pages)
Examines UK legal cases for evidence that the judiciary attaches importance
to Standard Statements of Accounting Practice; finds that it pays attention
 -rather than attach importance - to SSAPs, but where SSAPs and statute
diverge, choose to rely on statute.
*****
Contrarian marketing. A J Magrath in Across the Board (US), Oct 90 (5 pages)
Defines contrarian marketing as doing the opposite to conventional marketing
wisdom, quoting the example of Body Shop International, the UK cosmetics
group, which sells only through its own franchise outlets, uses minimal
packaging and does not advertise, educating customers rather than persuading
them. Offers other examples, mainly from the US, in industries as diverse as
window manufacture and theatre ownership, and examines the qualities that
contrarian marketers should possess.
*****
The new management: institutions for the information age. W E Halal in
Business in the Contemporary World (US), Winter 90 (14 pages)
Addresses the nature of management as society and business shifts from an
industrial to an information age; describes features of 'new management' -
smart growth, internal markets, participative leadership, multiple goals,
and strategic management. Wonders why, if there are such advantages from new
management, so many organisations stick to a traditional, bureaucratic
model; sees this lying in obstacles such as managers' unwillingness to yield
control (as they perceive it), yet the real situation to aim at is a mix of
freedom and control. Considers new management in social institutions -
government, medicine, education.
*****
Ethical values of individuals at different levels in an organisation. J R
Harris in Journal of Business Ethics (Netherlands), Sep 90 (10 pages)
Presents a study of individuals in the same firm: the objectives of the
study were - inter alia - to determine if significant differences existed at
different levels; and whether the organisation's culture affected values.
Warns against generalising results, but concludes - inter alia - that top
management may be less tolerant of fraudulent behaviour and that the longer
an individual is with a company the less tolerant he or she becomes. Appends
the business practice questionnaire used in the study; it contains 15
scenarios against which approval or disapproval is ranked.
*****
Projects in syndicate. Business Executive (UK), Mar/Apr 90 (2 pages)
Presents ideas of how to use syndicate projects to get trainees to draw upon
their own experience and knowledge in small groups that report back.
These abstracts are condensed from the abstracting journals published by
Anbar Management Publications. Licensed copies of the original articles may
be obtained at a cost of Pounds 5.75 each (including VAT and p+p; cash with
order) from Anbar, 62 Toller Lane, Bradford, West Yorkshire BD8 9BY.
</TEXT>
