FT  01 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: King challenged on MoD estimates -
Defence Questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Martin O'Neill, Labour's defence spokesman, yesterday challenged the
government to deny reports that Ministry of Defence estimates for
expenditure over the next ten years exceeded treasury forecasts by Pounds
21bn, Emma Tucker writes.
He demanded to know why there had been a delay in the publication of the
white paper this year and asked whether it was because 'long term costings
were now indicating that over the next decade there will be an overrun of
Pounds 21bn'.
Mr Tom King, the defence secretary, said Mr O'Neill was 'muddled'.
'He knows that the chief secretary has already confirmed that the defence
estimates for this year are likely to be Pounds 1.5bn above its originally
planned level,' said Mr King.
He said publication of the defence white paper had been delayed by the Gulf
War and he hoped to publish it before the summer. Earlier, he said the war
had cost Britain Pounds  1/2 bn.
Total expenditure had been around Pounds 2.5bn but Mr King said the
contributions made to those costs by other countries now exceeded Pounds
2bn.
Mr King also said that 20 British officers were serving with the UN mission
which would take full control of the demilitarised zone along the
Iraq/Kuwait border tomorrow.
Later, defence minister Mr Kenneth Carlisle said that the government was
looking at the future of all naval bases. It had, in addition, not yet
chosen the tank to replace the Chieftain as the army's main battle tank, but
hoped to make an announcement soon.
