<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Migrants halt decline in Scottish population
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE long-running gentle decline in the Scottish population was reversed last
year for the first time since the mid-1970s as Scotland, normally a reliable
source of emigrants, received an influx of migrants.
In the year to June 30 1990 the estimated population rose by 11,700 to
5,102,400, according to Scotland's registrar general.
A net 13,500 people migrated into Scotland, most of them from the rest of
Britain, but also from abroad.
This offset a natural fall in the population of 1,400 caused by a high
number of deaths from influenza in the winter of 1989-90 and a relatively
low number of births.
The gradual decline in the Scottish population and, until recently, high
levels of emigration have long been a matter of concern to the government,
as well as a source of political point scoring by opposition parties,
notably the Scottish National party.
</TEXT>
