<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Fimbra bids to regulate 'multi-tied' agents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL NUKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE troubled Financial Intermediaries, Managers and Brokers Regulatory
Association has thrown its hat in the ring as a potential supervisory body
of the 'multi-tied' financial advisers.
Such advisers are expected to emerge after the Securities and Investment
Board's review of the way packaged investment products are sold to the
public.
Mr Godfrey Jillings, chief executive of Fimbra, which supervises independent
financial advisers, said he would consider the creation of a new category of
'multi-tied' financial advisers if they were regulated by his organisation
and did not threaten the future viability of the independent sector.
Multi-tied advisers would sell several companies' products, standing between
independent advisers (who advise on all products on the market) and tied
agents (who sell only one company's products).
Mr Jillings stressed that his comments could not yet be interpreted as
Fimbra policy.
The Life Assurance and Unit Trust Regulatory Organisation is expected to
propose a formula under which all tied agents would come under its
jurisdiction.
However, Mr Jillings said that multi-tied advisers should not be regulated
by Lautro because it is responsible for product providers.
Recommendations on how banks should account for loans were proposed in a
draft statement put forward by the British Bankers Association yesterday.
The Statement of Recommended Accounting Practice (SORP) addresses issues
such as the valuation of advances, treatment of provisions, recognition of
interest and fees, and disclosure of concentrations of exposure. It
proposes, for example, that banks should list their exposure to countries
with financial problems.
The Statement of Recommended Accounting Practice, The British Bankers
Association, 10 Lombard Street, London EC3V 9EL. Free.
</TEXT>
