<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Japan steps up presence in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE manufacturers feel comfortable about their presence in Europe and
indicate that, to avoid conflict, localisation of operations and management
is essential, Emiko Terazono reports from Tokyo.
A recent survey of manufacturers, carried out by the Japan External Trade
Organisation (Jetro), showed the number of companies with at least 10 per
cent Japanese ownership operating in Europe increased to 676 at the end of
last January, a 27.8 per cent year-on-year rise.
Of these 676, 187 chose the UK as their base, 122 France, 109 Germany, and
64 Spain, 39 Italy, and 36 the Netherlands. The survey suggests the reasons
were ease of distribution, availability of English-speaking managers, a pool
of highly-skilled workers, and a well-developed infrastructure.
Almost half the companies responding expressed optimism about relationships
with their local communities. But some 20 per cent expressed concerns about
employee friction triggered by lack of localisation of management or by
implementation of Japanese-style management.
The main reasons cited for setting up operations in Europe were to avoid
problems with anti-dumping actions, to reinforce research and development in
Europe. Some 30 per cent said their operations followed acquiring an US
company with European links.
About 40 per cent said local content of purchased parts had increased, while
6.9 per cent claiming a decrease. In explaining the background to the
local-content increase, 32.7 per cent cited the improvement in the quality
of locally manufactured goods, 29.7 per cent increased in-house parts
manufacturing, with 24.8 per cent saying they had turned to buying parts
from Japanese suppliers in Europe.
Local personnel were assigned to a chief executive post in a third of the
companies, while director or managing director were the highest posts in a
quarter of the companies.
When asked about cultural and social community activities, 53.7 per cent
said they had no specific policy. Only 9.8 per cent said they were actively
sharing in community events under company direction.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
