<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Moscow now observer on Gatt dumping
committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DULLFORCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOVIET Union yesterday was granted observer status in Gatt's
Anti-Dumping Committee, marking a further step to eventual membership of the
world trade organisation. Last May, Moscow won observer status in Gatt
itself. In March this year, it won a similar standing on Gatt's import
licensing committee.
Yesterday's approval means Moscow has access to two of the codes, to which
Gatt members subscribe separately and which are meant mainly to lower
non-tariff obstacles to trade. Observer status means Soviet officials can
join talks, but not vote on decisions.
Mr Evgeny Makeyev, the Soviet ambassador, said Moscow considered it
important to be able to follow the anti-dumping committee's work because the
Soviet Union had just passed a new law on customs tariffs, which could allow
anti-dumping duties to be imposed.
Gatt's anti-dumping code lays down the conditions under which governments
may charge duties as a defence against 'dumped' imports. There are 25
signatories to the code, the EC counting as one. Moscow is expected to apply
next for observer status in the customs valuation committee which aims at
harmonising national valuation systems.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
