<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Beirut stirs cautiously beneath the ruins of 16 bloody
years: Lara Marlowe wanders through the rubble and talks to some great
survivors of a civil war that claimed 150,000 lives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LARA MARLOWE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIXTEEN years ago 27 Palestinians died at the hands of Christian Phalangist
militiamen in the Beirut suburb of Ain El-Roumaneh. Since then, Lebanon's
civil war has claimed 150,000 lives.
Yet today, the utter despair of the 1989 and 1990 'Aoun wars' - when
Christian leader General Michel Aoun attempted to take control of all of
Lebanon - is gone, and most Lebanese say cautiously that they believe their
civil war is over.
Ships now queue up outside Beirut port to unload their cargo. Tens of
thousands of Lebanese abroad have overwhelmed the rosters of Beirut schools
with enrolments for next September. Families are reclaiming summer homes in
the hills of Sofar, Aley and Chemlan, sometimes paying thousands of dollars
to dislodge their militia inhabitants. Shops are being refurbished with
chandeliers and marble facades.
Well-to-do Moslems venturing for the first time in many years to the Vieux
Quartier restaurant in Ashrafieh now comprise 20 per cent of the
establishment's clientele. 'No one becomes president without passing through
here,' Mr Rizkallah Akiki, the Vieux Quartier's maitre d'hotel, boasts.
But if Lebanon's finest restaurant has survived, so have its ghosts. There
is the table where President-elect, Mr Bashir Gemayel, sat with Mr Ariel
Sharon - then Israeli defence minister - before Mr Gemayel's assassination
in 1982.
Mr Dany Chamoun, son of the late President Camille Chamoun, who was
assassinated with his wife and sons last October, was an habitue. If you
hold your restaurant bill to the light, you can still see a triangle inside
a circle - the Phalangist symbol - blotted out. When President Elias Hrawi's
government ordered the Phalange to pull out of Ashrafieh in December, the
restaurant refused to continue paying the 5 per cent Phalangist militia tax.
'When the Christians were fighting the Christians last year, I knew the war
had to end,' Mr Akiki says. 'We hit the bottom of the abyss. I know many
people who died and it makes me sad. Why did it take 15 years? Why didn't
this solution come sooner?'
The solution is embodied in a fractious, 30-member cabinet officiating over
the lurching but, none the less, real implementation of the October 1989
Taif peace accords.
Mr Marwan Hamade, the minister of commerce, believes that the internal
political reasons for the war no longer exist. 'Religious animosity has
almost totally disappeared and has been replaced by power struggles within
each community,' he said. 'Psychologically, the Lebanese are so exhausted
that they have convinced themselves that whatever they have obtained from
the war is enough.'
He points out that economically, the country is incapable of generating a
financial base to continue the war. 'The militias skimmed off everything
there was to take. The Soviets won't send any more weapons to Jumblatt (the
Druze leader). The Saudis won't give money to the Palestinians and the
Israelis are not sending dollars to the Lebanese Forces (Phalange). Libya
has stopped helping the extremists. The Iranians may still be helping the
Hizbollah, but even their fervour has decreased - it's part of the general
weariness,' he said.
Many Lebanese believe the Gulf war helped their country. 'Because the
Americans and the Syrians are close now, the Americans are putting real
pressure on the Christian militias and the Syrians are putting pressure on
the Moslems,' Mr Hamade said.
President Hrawi's government is attempting to revive Lebanon's devastated
economy. The European Community and Saudi Arabia have given at least Dollars
820m in aid and soft loans but a government study estimates the cost of
reconstruction at Dollars 25bn.
A quarter of Lebanon's 3.5m population emigrated to escape the war and a
third of the remaining work force are unemployed.
In recent years, Lebanon has suffered triple-digit inflation and the
Lebanese pound has tumbled from 2.5 to the dollar in 1975, to a current rate
of 940.
The Lebanese government's priority has been to repair the electricity and
water works destroyed in the 'Aoun wars'. Residents of Beirut now receive an
average of six to 12 hours electricity each day as opposed to no electricity
at all a year ago.
Filling government coffers poses more of a challenge. Mr Hamade recently cut
an annual Dollars 80m wheat subsidy which had encouraged Lebanese to smuggle
wheat and flour abroad.
Other measures include the updating of pre-devaluation customs duty. From
yesterday - the latest deadline set for the disarming of all militias - the
government claims it will control, and tax, all ports in Lebanon. It will
also re-establish a tax on subsidised fuel, which accounted for nearly 20
per cent of government spending in 1989.
Symbols of a renascent Lebanon are everywhere. Mrs Rima Shehadeh, a Sunni
Moslem married to a Christian doctor, is one of the war's great survivors.
For 15 years, she and her husband, Najib, clung to his family's 125-year old
Ottoman stone mansion in the heart of west Beirut, moving from room to room
depending on the direction of the artillery fire as the militias
foughtacross their garden.
Mrs Rima Shehadeh continued her interior design business, sometimes taking
seven hours to cross on foot to east Beirut, a journey which now takes five
minutes. When roads were closed she transported furniture for clients in
vegetable carts.
'I always knew it was going to be worth it one day - if we survived
physically,' Mrs Shehadeh says. This year, six Lebanese bankers have
returned to Beirut and hired her to furnish their homes.
A few months before her death from cancer last year, Mrs Leila El-Hoss, the
wife of former prime minister Mr Selim El-Hoss and another Christian married
to a Moslem, visited Rima Shehadeh's home.
'The house which is alive in a country which is dead,' she wrote in the
guest book. Today that country appears to have been re-born.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
