<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 91 / Bonn ready to play greater world role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY IS prepared to assume greater international responsibilities, but is
not seeking amendments in the United Nations Charter which would allow it
become a permanent member of the Security Council, Mr Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, the foreign minister, said yesterday.
Mr Genscher, who had talks in London with Mr John Major, the British prime
minister, and Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, was clearly at pains
to counter criticisms that Germany was reluctant to assume the international
political responsibilities which its economic weight demanded.
'We do not want to renationalise our foreign policy,' Mr Genscher said,
emphasising that Germany intended to exercise its international
responsibilities through an integrated European Community. In the UN
Security Council, it was perfectly possible for Germany fully to express its
views to the two permanent members who were also members of the EC: Britain
and France.
He welcomed the fact that the British government under Mr Major was adopting
a more constructive attitude towards the development of the EC.
Stressing that a country's influence inside the Community was a reflection
of how positive a stand it adopted towards the EC, Mr Genscher said: 'We see
British policies are gaining weight and importance that further the
interests of the Community.'
He believed that an agreement on a common foreign and security policy would
be reached this year.
</TEXT>
