<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow drops after early rise on
March economic data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
CONCERTED computerised selling during the afternoon sparked a 50-point
turnround in the Dow Jones Industrial Average yesterday from a moderate rise
made earlier in the session on the back of positive US economic statistics,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow blue chip indicator was down 35.40 on balance at
2,876.98, having initially been over 15 points ahead. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 moved in similar fashion, ending 5.36 off at 373.66.
The Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter stocks, which had been lower all
day, registered a drop of 6.90 at 487.74.
Turnover on the New York SE was thin at just 150m shares. Declining issues
outpaced advances by more than two-to-one.
Share prices had been higher in early trading after the Commerce Department
released figures showing that new home sales rose by 1 per cent in March and
by a revised 18.6 per cent in February. Statistics outlining a 0.2 per cent
rise in personal income and a 0.6 per cent increase in personal consumption
in March were also released.
The figures were better than expected and suggested that economic activity
was picking up, albeit slowly. While this encouraged the stock market to
improve at first, the buying was never convincing and afternoon programme
selling quickly sent prices into retreat.
The market's losses in the past week, and the ease with which the Dow has
fallen through several technical support levels, has convinced many
professional investors that shares are embarking on a medium-term decline.
Only a cut in interest rates could bring the market out of its present
slide, said analysts.
Pepsico slipped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 30 1/4 on volume of 4.8m shares
after reporting a modest rise in first-quarter profits to 26 cents a share
from 23 cents.
A&amp;P, the supermarket group, dropped Dollars 4 to Dollars 45 3/4 in the wake
of Friday night's warning that its first-quarter profits might be as much as
30 per cent below the Dollars 1.33 a share earned at the same stage in 1990.
Boeing eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 45 3/4 on turnover of 2.2m shares after
revealing a modest rise in first-quarter income to 90 cents a share from the
year earlier level of 87 cents.
News of a Dollars 346m charge against earnings and a resultant Dollars 237m
first-quarter loss left USX, the steel and energy group, Dollars 1/2 lower
at Dollars 31 7/8 .
Vista Chemical climbed Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 52 1/8 in response to the
decision by RWE-DEA, the German utility group, to extend the deadline on its
Dollars 55 a share offer for Vista from May 13 to May 21.
Playboy Enterprises advanced Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 6 1/8 on reporting an
increase in fiscal third-quarter operating profits to 3 cents a share from
the 2 cents registered a year ago.
Other stocks to rise on news of improved profits included Universal
Corporation, up Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 31 1/4 , and Unum, Dollars  3/8
firmer at Dollars 62 1/2 .
Canada
TORONTO share prices drifted lower from the opening and accelerated their
fall late in the session on fears that the Ontario budget, the first by the
province's socialist-oriented New Democratic Party, would include a sharp
deficit and new taxes. Trading was moderate.
The composite index lost 25 points to close at 3,472.2, while declining
issues were ahead of rises by 351 to 176 after a volume of 21m shares.
Twelve of the 14 sub-groups finished lower, led by transportation, off 2.18
per cent, while gold issues declined 1.60 per cent and mining 1.45 per cent.
