<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / International Capital Markets: Campeau retailers unveil debt
restructure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FEDERATED Department Stores and Allied Stores, the two US retailing groups
owned by Canada's Campeau Corporation but operating under the protection of
Chapter 11 of the US Bankruptcy Code since 1990, yesterday filed their 'plan
of reorganisation' with the bankruptcy court.
The much-publicised bankruptcies came to symbolise the end of the leveraged
bid wave which engulfed corporate America in the Eighties. Campeau's Dollars
10bn acquisitions of Allied and Federated in 1986 and 1988 respectively
turned sour a few years later when the two were unable to service debt which
funded the purchase.
In the plan filed in Cincinnati yesterday, the retail groups - which take in
the prestigious Bloomingdale's store in Manhattan - said they hoped to
emerge from protection early next year.
The aim is to give creditors a mixture of cash, new debt securities, and
equity in a retail group formed by the merger of Federated and Allied. These
shares would probably be listed.
Some Dollars 8.2bn of claims - the figure at the time of the bankruptcy
filing - would be 'compromised', so the business could emerge with debts of
Dollars 2.8bn and equity of Dollars 2.3bn.
General unsecured claims against Federated and Allied would receive shares
in the merged group; general unsecured claims against subsidiaries would
receive a mixture of cash and new medium-term notes. Claims against
Federated Stores Inc (FSI), the immediate parent company of Federated
Department Stores and Allied Stores would be satisfied by distributing stock
in Ralphs, a Los Angeles-based supermarket subsidiary of FSI. Campeau, a
leading FSI creditor, would receive 14.79 per cent of Ralphs. Another 8.6
per cent would go to Bank of Montreal and Banque Paribas.
The companies stressed yesterday that the plan does not have approval of any
creditors, although it said that some key concepts were discussed with them.
</TEXT>
