<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Government Bonds: Bunds hold nerve after G-7 interest rate
pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE GERMAN government bond market showed resilience yesterday following
calls for lower global interest rates from the weekend meeting of finance
ministers of the Group of Seven industrialised countries.
The benchmark 9 per cent 10-year Bund closed yesterday at 103.86, for a
yield of 8.39 per cent, against 8.41 per cent on Friday. On the London
International Financial Futures Exchange, the long bund futures contract
closed at 85.42, against 85.19 at Friday's close.
Although the G-7 statement contained a commitment to lower global interest
rates in the longer term, there is no sign that the German authorities will
ease monetary conditions. Indeed, figures released yesterday confirmed that
inflationary pressures persist within the German economy.
Money supply data for March showed the M3 measure of broad money growing at
a yearly rate of 4.4 per cent over the last quarter of 1990, for a
year-on-year increase of 20.3 per cent over the first quarter last year.
Statistics also showed inflation rising in March by 0.5 per cent over
February, for an annualised rate of 2.8 per cent, against 2.5 per cent last
time.
Moreover, money market conditions remain tight. Yesterday German call money
interest rates were only just below the 9 per cent Lombard rate, the
Bundesbank emergency funding rate.
Hence the bund market will watch Thursday's Bundesbank council meeting in
anticipation of higher, rather than lower, interest rates. Analysts will be
watching industrial production and manufacturing orders figures this week
for signs of overheating.
However, yesterday the Bundesbank signalled that it would supply short-term
liquidity to the market at an unchanged fixed rate of 8.6 per cent at its
regular repurchase operations today. This might indicate that any tightening
of monetary conditions will be postponed beyond this week.
Lex, Page 22
US GOVERNMENT bond prices eased after a variety of economic data provided a
mixed view of the state of the economy.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year Treasury issue was down  7/32 at 96
1/16 , to carry a yield of 8.224 per cent. The short end was also weaker,
with the two-year note  1/32 lower at 100 3/16 , to yield 6.881 per cent.
Among the welter of economic statistics, it was the 0.6 per cent gain in
personal consumption for March that created the biggest stir. The rise was
larger than forecast and, allied to a 0.2 per cent rise in personal income
during the period, suggested that the economic recovery was gradually
picking up pace.
The market was also surprised by figures showing new home sales rose 1 per
cent in March, and a revised 18.6 per cent in February. New home sales are
traditionally regarded as a useful indicator of future economic trends.
Any evidence of an economic upturn strengthens the hands of those at the
Federal Reserve who see no further need for an interest rate cut, and who
believe policy should be left unchanged to prevent a return to high
inflation.
Activity through the day was light, although in the afternoon bond prices
fell further on reports of a large seller of bond futures contracts and a
large seller of two-year notes.
In the credit markets, the Fed intervened to push the Fed funds rate back up
to its target of 6 per cent.
UK GOVERNMENT bonds weakened slightly, continuing the upward correction in
yields seen on Friday in the face of sterling's weakness on the foreign
exchange markets.
The benchmark 11 3/4 per cent gilt maturing 2003/2007 closed down just 1/16
of a point on the day at 109 31/32 for a yield of 10.258 per cent. The long
gilt futures contract closed at 91.17, after opening at 91.20.
The market is focusing on Thursday's local government elections for pointers
to the timing and outcome of a general election expected this year. The
Confederation of British Industry industrial trends survey for March,
released today, is expected to show a marginal upturn in business confidence
and an improvement in forward indicators.
JAPANESE government bonds moved higher in London in lacklustre trading, with
the Tokyo market closed for a public holiday. The benchmark government bond
issue No 129 closed on a yield of 6.71 per cent, against 6.74 per cent on
Friday.
Although trading is likely to remain thin for the rest of the week, analysts
are watching for signs of the Bank of Japan's reaction to G-7 pressures for
lower global interest rates.
THE DUTCH government raised Fl 1.6bn through tap sales of its 8.5 per cent
bond due 2006 yesterday. The tap price was lowered to 99.40 from 99.55 on
Friday, raising the yield by two basis points to 8.57 per cent.
The sales brought the total raised to Fl 3.1bn since the tap sale was opened
last Thursday.
