<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / International Company News: Arco posts earnings decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ATLANTIC Richfield (Arco), the Los Angeles-based oil and gas company,
yesterday posted a decline in underlying first-quarter earnings, in line
with its earlier predictions, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
Arco's 1990 results were distorted by a Dollars 323m gain from a change in
accounting methods and Dollars 233m after-tax charges relating to
environmental clean-up costs and tax provisions.
Including these one-time items, Arco's net income for the first three months
of 1991 dropped 41 per cent to Dollars 351m or Dollars 2.17 a share from
Dollars 592m or Dollars 3.55 a year earlier.
Mr Lodwrick Cook, chairman, said the first-quarter results reflected
unseasonably low natural gas prices, lower average crude oil prices and
lower margins and volume for chemical operations. These more than offset
stronger refining results and higher crude oil and natural gas production
levels.
Arco's worldwide oil and gas exploration and production operations earned
Dollars 261m after tax, down 19 per cent from Dollars 319m a year ago.
Refining and marketing earned Dollars 74m against Dollars 72m.
</TEXT>
