<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / International Company News: US steel companies suffer from
recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THREE leading US steel companies yesterday reported first quarter losses as
the US recession hit demand for their products, particularly in the
automotive and consumer white goods markets.
USX, the largest steel manufacturer in the US, reported a first-quarter net
loss of Dollars 237m, or 94 cent a share, compared with net income of
Dollars 176m, or 66 cents a share, in the first quarter of last year. Sales
were Dollars 4.5bn, against Dollars 4.7bn. The figures included Dollars 346m
of one-time restructuring charges.
Its steel business reported an operating loss of Dollars 502m, or Dollars
180m without restructuring charges, but its Marathon energy operations
produced operating income of Dollars 229m, including a Dollars 24m
restructuring charge, aided by a strong downstream performance.
Mr Charles Corry, the chairman, said the downstream energy business should
be helped by the coming summer driving season. No appreciable improvement in
steel prices was expected until the second half, but the steel division's
second quarter results were expected to improve.
LTV, the third largest US steel group, reported a first quarter net loss of
Dollars 46.3m on sales of Dollars 1.43bn, compared with income of Dollars
44.2m in the same period of last year on sales of Dollars 1.49bn. The loss
per share was 46 cents, against earnings last year of 32 cents.
LTV's steel operations reported a first quarter operating loss of Dollars
48.8m, before restructuring charges, compared with operating income of
Dollars 41.1m in the first quarter of 1990.
National Steel, the fifth largest US manufacturer, reported a net loss of
Dollars 64.4m in the first quarter on sales of Dollars 524m, compared to a
net loss of Dollars 4.2m on sales of Dollars 612m in 1990.
</TEXT>
