<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / International Company News: IBM fails to see any sign of
market improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines, which earlier this month reported a 50 per
cent drop in first-quarter earnings, said yesterday that it had not yet seen
any sign of an improvement in the market outlook.
The downbeat assessment of global business conditions by the world's largest
computer manufacturer follows expressions of doubt about the strength of the
expected US economic recovery from companies in several large US sectors
over the past few weeks.
Mr John Akers, IBM chairman, told the company's annual meeting that the war
in the Gulf and economic problems worldwide had made the business
environment increasingly difficult - not just in North America but in Europe
and Asia as well.
During the quarter many customers had deferred buying decisions and product
installations. This had been felt fairly uniformly across IBM's product line
and around the world but particularly in the US and in its large systems.
'How long this cautious approach by our customers will last is hard to
tell,' Mr Akers said. 'Our operating rates will only improve when our
customers' confidence about their business improves.
'We have seen no evidence yet to indicate any improvement in the near term,
and consequently the year remains uncertain.'
For the first quarter IBM reported net earnings of Dollars 500m, down from
the Dollars 1bn earned in the same period of last year, on revenues down 4.5
per cent at Dollars 13.5bn. The figures disappointed Wall Street, despite
IBM's earlier warning of a sharp drop.
Analysts were particularly surprised at the depth of the fall in its
hardware sales and some questioned whether this was entirely due to general
economic conditions.
Yesterday Mr Akers said the future of the computing industry remained bright
for those who managed their business well and IBM must prepare to take best
advantage of the eventual economic improvement.
IBM shares fell Dollars 2 1/2 in on the New York Stock Exchange to stand at
Dollars 107 3/8 at lunchtime.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 29
</PAGE>
