FT  30 APR 91 / UK Company News: Norton launches probe into US and German
arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOLLOWING the resignation of Mr James Tildesley as chairman and chief
executive of Norton Group on Friday, the revamped board has launched an
investigation into the US and German subsidiaries.
Norton said yesterday that 'strenuous inquiries' were being made into the
financial and trading position of Pro-Fit Piping, in the US, and FUS, the
German subsidiary.
The Pounds 8.2m purchase of FUS, a fasteners maker, caused controversy
because the vendor was a Channel Islands trust company set up to benefit Mr
Tildesley's offspring.
His former company, PSM, had founded the German business and a poorly
supported Pounds 6.5m rights issue to help complete the purchase had a
troubled conclusion in January.
The company, which is best known for its motorcycle business, is being
investigated by the Department of Trade and and Industry.
Its shares were suspended at 18p on April 1 because of a delay in publishing
results for the six months to October 31.
