<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Etam threatened by SA takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FAMILY that controls one of South Africa's largest women's fashion
chains has taken the first public step towards a possible bid for Etam, the
UK fashion chain.
Oceana Investment Corporation, a vehicle for the Lewis family, which owns
the 700-store Foschini chain in South Africa, has made a tender offer of up
to Pounds 22.3m for 18.5 per cent of Etam's shares. This would take its
stake to 25.1 per cent.
The maximum price offered is 185p per share, putting a market value of
Pounds 121m on Etam. This compares with Pounds 114.3m at yesterday's closing
price of 175p, up 15p.
Mr Michael Lewis, a director of Oceana and Foschini, said Oceana was
considering making an offer for the whole of Etam. It did not want to make a
hostile bid and the tender offer was a way of gauging shareholder response.
Etam responded angrily to the move, describing it as 'an attempt to gain
back-door control at an unacceptably low price.' The board had already
rebuffed a cash and shares takeover proposal, worth about 150p a share, from
Oceana early this year.
Mr Alan Howard, chairman, said: 'Oceana is aiming to profit at our
shareholders' expense from the very significant benefits still to flow
through from Etam's substantial investment over the last three years and the
upturn to come in the retail cycle.'
Over the past four years Etam has invested Pounds 78m to increase floorspace
by 60 per cent. It has added the Snob teenage fashion and Peter Brown
menswear shops to its portfolio as well as expanding the established Etam
and Tammy Girl chains. Turnover has increased by more than 80 per cent to
Pounds 206.5m.
But the 1990-91 results announced last week showed a 51 per cent fall in
profit to Pounds 8.5m (Pounds 17.5m), which compares with the record Pounds
17.9m set back in 1987-88. The figure was the worst since 1983-84. However,
after a first-half loss of Pounds 1.1m, Mr Howard said the management had
proved its ability by effecting a dramatic second-half recovery in adverse
market conditions.
Mr Lewis said that if a bid were launched for Etam, it would be at a maximum
price of 185p. This was nearly 25 times the earnings per share announced
last week and 15 to 20 times this year's earnings forecasts.
The offer for up to 12.1m shares is being made by Campbell Lutyens Hudson,
the investment bank, on behalf of Oceana Retail Holdings, set up for the
purpose. The closing date is May 7 and the striking price will depend on the
number of shares subscribed.
</TEXT>
