FT  30 APR 91 / Managers at Brent Walker bid for brewery and pubs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGEMENT at Brent Walker, the heavily-borrowed leisure group, yesterday
offered to buy out the company's brewing operations and several pubs.
Mr Alistair Arkley, the managing director of Brent Walker Brewing and
Trading and leader of the buy-out team, said it was hoped that 'the company
will view favourably this firm offer against other options which it is
understood to be considering'.
Allied-Lyons, the food and drinks group, said last week that it had been
discussing a possible deal with Brent Walker. One suggestion was that Allied
could agree to supply Brent Walker's 1,122 pubs, putting extra volume
through its own six breweries.
Such a move might involve the closure of Brent Walker's Camerons brewery in
Hartlepool, which employs a staff of 400. Union representatives from the
brewery yesterday delivered a petition against such a move, signed by 20,000
Hartlepool residents, to the company.
Camerons' main beer brand, Strongarm, is sold mainly in the Teesside area.
Mr Arkley said yesterday that his buy-out team, which includes the
division's finance, production and commercial directors and is being advised
by accountants, Price Waterhouse, had secured support from several banks and
institutions.
An 'indicative offer' had been made to Brent Walker for the brewery and
several pubs in the locality. The team is awaiting further negotiations.
The buy-out team declined to reveal the value of the offer.
Brent Walker, which is due to publish its 1990 accounts next month, is
working with its bankers on a restructuring of liabilities. The leisure
group must raise cash and prune operations to service its Pounds 1.4bn debt.
It has been discussing the sale of various assets for some time.
There have been reports that some bankers are pressing for the sale of the
William Hill betting shops chain. Brent Walker still owes Pounds 50m on the
Pounds 615m purchase price from Grand Metropolitan, the UK drinks, food and
retailing group.
Brent Walker's board has been restructured since the group ran into
difficulties. Lord Kindersley became non-executive chairman in January, and
Mr Nicholas Ward, former chairman and chief executive of the healthcare
group, Macarthy, was appointed group managing director.
