<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Royal Mail may open its network to private couriers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POST Office is considering opening up its postal network to private
couriers.
The Royal Mail, the Post Office's letter service, is looking at proposals to
introduce more competition in anticipation of the European Commission's
green paper on liberalising postal services, due to be published in June.
The Royal Mail, which has a monopoly on all letters on which postage is
below Pounds 1, is compiling details of the cost of sending a letter to
enable it to draw up a pricing structure for the use of its services.
Private couriers such as TNT, the Australian delivery company, and DHL, the
international courier, might seek to carry mail and then, in rural areas, be
able to pay the Post Office network to deliver their letters on the final
leg through the Royal Mail.
The concept is similar to inter-connection in the telecommunications
industry, where long-distance telephone companies, such as Mercury, can pay
British Telecom to route the final part of a call.
The move by the Royal Mail to conduct a detailed account of its costs
follows the disclosure that the Department of Trade and Industry is looking
into the Post Office's finances as a prelude to possible privatisation.
Mr Bill Cockburn, managing director of the Royal Mail, said: 'In order to be
able to offer a delivery network to other companies we want to have a more
detailed understanding of our costs.
'If a company has no presence in a particular part of the country then we
may be able to offer them our services for the right price.'
Mr Alan Jones, managing director of TNT, said: 'This is a very interesting
idea. We will monitor it with great interest.'
However, private couriers may only decide to make full use of the Post
Office's services if the government abolishes, or reduces, its monopoly on
letters under Pounds 1.
Mr Cockburn disclosed that the Royal Mail is conducting its investigation of
costs with the Post Office Users' National Council, a government watchdog,
which will have confidential access to all the figures.
Mr George Brown, a member of the council's executive, said: 'We hope to get
to the bottom of how every penny of the first and second class stamp is
spent.'
Meanwhile, the Post Office published figures showing that 85 per cent of
first class letters arrive the day after posting, representing a 7.4 per
cent improvement in first class mail reliability.
Postal ballot, Page 13
Telecom tariff, Page 10
</TEXT>
