<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Boycott threat to university exams
recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ASSOCIATION of Uni-versity Teachers (AUT) has backed away from
industrial action in pursuit of this year's pay claim.
Results of the ballot of university lecturers, declared yesterday, showed
only a small majority in favour of industrial action, making an examination
boycott now unlikely. On a low turnout - 42 per cent - a majority of only
1,310 favoured boycotting the marking of university exams. The total poll
was less than 13,000.
'University staff are grossly underpaid,' said Ms Diana Warwick, AUT general
secretary. 'Our claim for a 16 per cent increase was, and is, fair and
moderate, but in seeking to achieve our aim our members wish to act
reasonably and professionally.'
University employers last week imposed an interim settlement of 5 per cent
outside the normal negotiating machinery. No further meetings with the union
have been arranged.
The AUT claim for 16 per cent was part of a three-year strategy to make up
for a long-term shortfall in lecturers' salaries.
The AUT executive decided yesterday to seek an urgent meeting with Mr
Kenneth Clarke, education secretary, to discuss extending to lecturers the
pay review body already promised to school teachers.
Ms Warwick kept open the possibility of industrial action should 'all
avenues' of resolving the pay dispute prove unsuccessful. The issue will be
debated at the union's conference next month.
The AUT will concentrate instead on pressing the case for a new method of
salary determination for academic staff.
</TEXT>
