<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Equal opportunities staff 'among the
most stressed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EQUAL opportunities person-nel, who have the task of implementing policies
on race, sex and disability within organisations, are among the most
stressed of all occupational groups, according to a survey published today.
Above-average levels of physical ill health were found in 90 per cent of
equal opportunities managers and their staff, and nearly 75 per cent showed
above-average levels of mental ill health, the study by occupational
psychologists found.
More than 30 per cent of EO workers saw no career development if they stayed
in the field and nearly 23 per cent indicated that they wanted to leave
their present employers.
Pearn Kandola Downs, the group of psychologists that carried out the survey,
found the greatest sources of stress were lack of clarity about job function
and interpersonal relations, particularly in dealing with people who may
feel threatened by EO policies.
Equal Opportunities Can Damage Your Health. Available from Pearn Kandola
Downs, 76 Banbury Road, Oxford OX2 6JT. Pounds 22 (incl p&amp;p).
</TEXT>
