FT  30 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Labour plan for change in 'macho'
management - City Policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR government would seek to change Britain's management culture to
make company boards more accountable to employees and curb directors' pay
rises, Ms Marjorie Mowlam, the party's City spokesman said last night, Ralph
Atkins writes.
Company directors have become like 'medieval barons', willingly reducing
their accountability, Ms Mowlam said. Britain was far more restrictive that
other European Community countries.
'The macho management culture of the 1980s, characterised by toughness and
autocratic attitudes, is all too common. It manifests itself in the relative
loss of power by employees and the generally inadequate response to training
and R&amp;D'
She used a speech to the London Bullion Markets Association to attack recent
large pay rises for directors. Few boards would consider taking a pay cut to
reflect declining returns to shareholders.
Directors pay rises have outstripped those of other employees for at least
the last five years and were often 'disproportionate' to the actual benefits
which shareholders received, Ms Mowlam said. 'Few shareholders bothered to
question such handsome rewards.'
Ms Mowlam said cuts in the top rate of income tax to 40p were intended to
improve incentives. 'However many directors took it upon themselves to cream
off even more of the profits with record pay awards in 1989, the first year
of the lower tax rates. This was a blatant abuse of the original intention.'
</TEXT>
