FT  30 APR 91 / Propeller designs for successor to QE2 under test
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SWEDISH subsidiary of Vickers, the UK engineering group, is testing
propeller designs for a possible Cunard ocean liner that may become the
successor to the 23-year-old QE2.
Cunard Lines, owned by Trafalgar House, the UK conglomerate, yesterday
described as 'entirely speculative' a newspaper report of a top-secret
project, codenamed Q5, to design a liner to replace the QE2.
It is known that KaMeWa, of Sweden, part of Vickers' marine engineering
division, is studying propeller designs for a model of a Cunard liner.
KaMeWa, acquired by Vickers in 1986, has one of the world's largest
facilities for research into propulsion technology.
Yesterday Trafalgar House said it was always looking at a variety of
possible ways forward for Cunard, but otherwise had no comment on the
report. The company said it would not speak about its fleet plans until the
appropriate time.
If the project were to go ahead, UK shipyards would face strong competition
for the order from continental European yards that have specialised in
cruise ships. It is understood that the liner would not be bigger than the
QE2, in order that it could pass through the Panama Canal.
The report, in the Sunday Express, quoted an estimate by industry experts
that a new liner would cost Cunard Pounds 400m.
Trafalgar House described the report as longer on imagination than hard
fact. Industry sources are quoted saying the ship would become the Princess
Diana - or, depending on how long the project takes, the Queen Diana.
KaMeWa is the world's biggest manufacturer of controllable-pitch propellers.
On this kind of propeller, the angle at which the blades rotate can be
altered, changing the speed or direction of the ship, whereas conventional
propellers are turned by a shaft of varying speed.
</TEXT>
