<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / University financing is criticised as outdated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIVERSITIES came under attack yesterday from a former member of Mrs
Thatcher's policy unit.
Professor Sir Douglas Hague, chairman of the Economic and Social Science
Research Council, criticised the financing of universities and their
structure and culture as outdated in a study published by the Institute of
Economic Affairs.
He says in the report: 'Universities will have to be like businesses and
learn to pay twice as much to half as many people.'
Attacking excessive specialisation among academics, Sir Douglas says:
'Buttressed in their academic bunker . . . they presume greater mastery of
limited fields, perhaps never recalling the old saw about knowing everything
about nothing.'
He recommends changes in the system including abolishing national university
pay scales, a shift from grants to fees, and an increase in the number of
institutions able to award degrees.
Beyond Universities. IEA, 2 Lord North Street, London SW1P 3LB. Pounds 6.95.
