<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Docklands body to cut 40% of staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE London Docklands Development Corporation, the government-funded
regeneration body, yesterday announced plans to shed 40 per cent of its
staff over the next two years.
The corporation, which has 456 staff, expects to make half the cuts by the
end of next March.
High staff turnover and short-term contracts will limit numbers of
compulsory redundancies needed. The corporation said no decision had been
made on where the redundancies might fall.
The decision follows a long review of the corporation's role and staffing
needs.
The review, which was approved 10 days ago, called for a new management
structure. It involves the appointment of several assistant chief executives
and senior managers to focus on specific tasks and the pooling of the rest
of the staff into a 'task-orientated resource group'.
The recession in the property market, which was earlier and more severe in
the Docklands than virtually any other part of the country, has created
financial difficulties for the corporation.
Heavy spending on transport schemes meant that in the year ended March 31
1990, expenditure of Pounds 279m exceeded income by Pounds 4.2m. At the year
end, it had a cash balance of more than Pounds 3m and reserves in excess of
Pounds 115m.
The corporation said that the commissioning of the staffing review pre-dated
the arrival of Mr Eric Sorensen, a civil servant from the Department of the
Environment, who became chief executive two months ago.
</TEXT>
