<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Judge to rule on aircraft hit by tractor
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A HIGH court action to determine liability for Dollars 1m (Pounds 600,000)
damage allegedly caused when a runaway tractor hit a US Air Force aircraft
began yesterday.
The Trackair tractor collided with the left wing of the stationary TR1
spyplane at RAF Alconbury, Cambridgeshire, in December 1987.
Two companies face the US government in the five-day hearing to determine
liability. The court will decide whether the owner or the user of the
tractor should pay the bill.
ARC Construction of Abingdon, Oxfordshire, the user, and HS Isis Hire, of
Redditch, Hereford and Worcester, the owner, both deny negligence.
Mr Charles Falconer, QC, told Mr Justice Hobhouse that ARC was using the
tractor for asphalt work at the airfield. Its driver left the vehicle
without its handbrake on and with no chocks in front of its wheels.
The tractor moved off without the driver, who chased after it trying in vain
to clamber into the cab. The aircraft's pilot could only release its brakes
to reduce the impact.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
