<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Peruvian banking and finance liberalised by new law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Peruvian financial system is to be shaken up in favour of market forces
after the first big change in the country's banking law for 60 years.
The new law, promulgated last week by President Alberto Fujimori, lets
financial institutions to set their own interest rates and reopens the
country to foreign banks. It also lets public sector companies become
clients of private banks.
This has been well received in general by local banks, finance institutions
and insurance companies.
In an attempt to curb the parallel or informal banks which have mushroomed
in Peru over the past few years, the law gives banks, finance and insurance
houses three months to constitute themselves as limited companies or
co-operatives.
Institutions will have, however, two years to meet the minimum capital
requirements under the new regulations.
The new law curbs the power of the Central Reserve Bank. It will no longer
fix interest rates. They will be determined by the market, with the BCR
setting a top limit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2419</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BD3BIADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Japan sees new SDRs easing liquidity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN yesterday provided the first details of its proposal to enhance global
financial resources through an issue of Special Drawing Rights, the reserve
asset created and managed by the International Monetary Fund.
Mr Ryutaro Hashimoto, Japanese finance minister, told the IMF's
policy-making Interim Committee that he would like to see a selective SDR
allocation to help countries in the Third World, and central and eastern
Europe, suffering from temporary liquidity problems.
He said any new SDRs should be given to countries implementing economic
reform programmes, and be linked to the acceptance of strict economic
conditions in those recipient countries.
In this way, the Japanese minister went some way towards deflecting
criticism of his proposals from countries such as the US and Germany, which
have always considered that a new allocation of SRDs would be unnecessary
and potentially inflationary.
Mr Hashimoto's proposal won some support from Mr Pierre Be're'govoy, French
finance minister, yesterday.
He said that an issue of 30bn SDRs (Dollars 40bn), on top of the existing
21.4bn SDRs held by IMF member countries, would increase world reserve
assets by only about 5 per cent and therefore would not be inflationary.
Earlier, however, Mr Karl Otto Pohl, president of the German Bundesbank,
said he was thoroughly opposed to any new SDR allocation.
He said that such a move would amount to a falsification of the character of
the SDR, which had been created originally to offset a shortage of
liquidity. At present, there was no shortage of liquidity in the world, Mr
Pohl added.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2420</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BD3BIADWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910430
