<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / UN says Kurds heading home in their thousands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS at The UN and Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations said yesterday that Kurdish refugees who fled Iraq were
returning home at the rate of almost 20,000 a day but a lack of cash could
affect its ability to respond.
It also said it would look at the costs and logistics of taking over camps
in safe havens set up in northern Iraq by US, British, French and other
western troops.
'We were very impressed with the significant number of people who were
returning in the Sulaimaniya and Irbil regions (in northern Iraq),' Mr Bernd
Bernander, co-ordinator of a UN relief operation in Iraq, said in Baghdad.
There were indications last night that the numbers of returning Kurds were
growing after Kurdish guerrilla leaders lifted a roadblock barring their way
down the mountains from Turkey. This followed a meeting between the
guerrillas, or peshmerga, and allied military commanders who urged that
civilians should not be hindered from returning to the town of Zakho, where
a protected refugee camp has been set up.
Kurdish leaders had denied that they have a policy of preventing refugees
from leaving the mountains on the Turkish border and going to Zakho, but
acknowledged that they were still concerned about the presence of some 50
Iraqi policemen in the area.
At the United Nations last night Iraq's ambassador Abdul Amir al-Anbari said
his government was likely to disapprove of a British proposal for a UN
police force to replace the allied troops in northern Iraq. Speaking as
Britain asked fellow members of the Security Council to back the plan, he
said that such action would be 'naked intervention'. He said a recent
agreement between Baghdad and the Kurds made the presence of foreign troops
irrelevant. Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has said that returning Kurds
need not fear reprisal.
Britain hoped to obtain broad Security Council agreement for its plan
without the need for a formal resolution, diplomats said.
Following discussions with representatives of the US and France, which
support the initiative, Sir David Hannay, the UK ambassador to the UN,
planned to broaden the consultations to include the Soviet Union and China.
President Turgut Ozal of Turkey said it was essential for the allies to
remain in northern Iraq to give confidence to the returning Kurds.
'If the allied powers do not maintain their presence in northern Iraq, the
Iraqi Kurds will start running again as soon as they see an Iraqi soldier,'
he told the Iranian news agency.
More UK aid, Page 12
