FT  30 APR 91 / Poland cuts base rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND'S base interest rate will be cut tomorrow to 59 per cent from 72 per
cent. It was increased from 55 per cent in January as part of the
government's tight-money policy to combat annual inflation of 250 per cent
at the end of 1990.
The government is now expecting 55 per cent inflation this year against an
earlier forecast of 36 per cent.
The privatisation minister, Mr Janusz Lewandowski, said yesterday that the
country's next public share offer would open around May 20 with the sale of
the Swarzedz furniture factory near Poznan. Five per cent of the shares are
to be given to three former owners of workshops taken over after the war to
set up the factory.
The ministry is also expected to sign an agreement at the same time selling
51 per cent of the Polkolor television works to Thomson of France for
Dollars 35m.
