<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Dollar hits high against D-Mark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR yesterday hit its highest levels against the D-Mark in Europe for
16 months, amid signs that the world's leading nations are happy to see the
currency continue its recent rise.
Although the currency slipped in New York on profit-taking, European foreign
exchange dealers had been encouraged to buy the dollar because the Group of
Seven leading industrial nations failed to mention its persistent strength
in their final statement after a weekend meeting in Washington.
While the US failed in its short-term goal of persuading Germany to cut its
interest rates, the discussions among the finance ministers and central bank
governors of the US, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada are
expected to lead to lower interest rates in coming months.
US officials have pressed for easier borrowing conditions worldwide, as part
of an effort to spur economic growth.
Although the dollar closed below the day's highs, it kept up the momentum
which has seen it jump by 22 per cent against the D-Mark since hitting an
all-time trading low against the Germany currency in mid-February.
The dollar's rise has been due to increasing optimism about the outlook for
the US economy, while the D-Mark has been affected by worries about the
economic cost of German re-unification.
The German currency's recent weakness has worried the Bundesbank, which
wants a strong D-Mark to constrain inflationary pressures.
Last night, the dollar closed in London at DM1.769, up more than 1 pfennig
on Friday's close. At the start of trading in Frankfurt, it was quoted at
DM1.786, its highest opening there since December, 1989. Later in New York,
it eased to close at Dollars 1.7512.
On the lack of reference to the dollar in the G7 communique, Mr Jim O'Neill,
head of financial markets research at Swiss Bank Corporation in London,
said: 'It seems that, outside Germany, no one is worried by the low D-Mark.'
