<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Economy to recover soon says Lamont: Chancellor predicts
significant strengthening of UK position as inflation falls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said yesterday that economic recovery in
Britain was 'round the corner'.
The UK was making 'excellent progress' in cutting inflation, Mr Lamont told
journalists just after addressing the policy-making interim committee of the
International Monetary Fund in Washington.
'I think we are going to get inflation down to a level not so far removed
from the strongest countries in Europe within a very short period of time,'
he said. It would result in a very significant strengthening of the UK
position.
Mr Lamont said he could not be precise about the timing of the recovery,
although he thought it would be around the end of the second quarter. In the
UK, as elsewhere, lower inflation and lower interest rates would be powerful
forces for recovery. The 'key lesson of the late 1980s' was that firm
control over inflation was a condition for sustained growth.
He repeated the government's position that it would cut interest rates when
reduced inflation created the flexibility for such action.
He dismissed as 'imaginative' a Sunday newspaper report that interest rates
would be cut again next month. 'I have made no commitment on cutting rates,'
he said.
The chancellor's upbeat assessment of Britain's economic prospects came only
days before Thursday's local elections and after a period in which economic
news has been almost universally bad.
He said that in the coming months the official statistics - particularly
those for lagging indicators such as employment and investment - would
continue providing evidence of past weakness in the economy.
But he stressed the importance of distinguishing such backward looking
indicators from forward looking signs that were now emerging. These, he
said, had begun to show a marked improvement in consumer and business
confidence.
Mr Lamont admitted that unemployment would continue to rise during this
year, although the extent would depend on the level of wage settlements and
on the effectiveness of the government's labour market reforms. He said that
such reforms could have made the labour market more flexible and there were
indications that wage increases might be moderating.
The chancellor's comments follow the optimism expressed recently by Mr John
Major about an economic recovery on the horizon - although even some
Conservative MPs at Westminster are not yet convinced.
The steep rises in unemployment are increasingly dominating clashes between
the main parties at Westminster, with the government's handling of the
economy high on the political agenda.
Last night, Mr Gordon Brown, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, said:
'Far from turning the corner, all the evidence is that unemployment will
rise fast during spring and the summer, that manufacturing investment will
fall by 17 per cent this year and our industrial capacity is now being
eroded in the run up to 1992.'
Mr Lamont, addressing the IMF committee on trade issues, said that removing
barriers had a vital part to play in giving the world a non-inflationary
boost. A resumption of negotiations in the Uruguay Round of trade
liberalisation talks was 'vital' and it was 'particularly important' that
there should be less protection of agriculture in the European Community and
elsewhere.
He also called on the world's industrialised nations to apply existing rules
under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) and to operate
export credit schemes on an unsubsidised basis.
The provision of export credit that could not be fully repaid had involved a
large sacrifice by taxpayers in creditor countries, the chancellor said. It
constituted a form of government interference in free trade that was
damaging to growth and efficiency in developed and developing countries
alike.
Mr Lamont said the UK would charge higher premiums for taking on risk and be
more cautious about extending guarantees. He hoped other countries would do
the same.
M&amp;S job cuts, Page 22
</TEXT>
