<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / International Company News: LTV hit by downturn in cars and
appliances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LTV, the third largest US steel group, yesterday reported a first-quarter
net loss of Dollars 46.3m, which it blamed on a slump in demand for cars and
household appliances.
LTV, which has been operating under the protection of the US bankruptcy
courts since 1986, is the latest in a succession of US steel manufacturers
to report first-quarter losses stemming from the North American economic
downturn.
The net loss, on sales of Dollars 1.43bn, compared with income of Dollars
44.2m on sales of Dollars 1.49bn last time. The loss per share was 46 cents,
against earnings last year of 32 cents.
LTV's steel operations reported a first-quarter operating loss of Dollars
48.8m, before restructuring charges, against operating income of Dollars
41.1m in the first quarter of 1990.
Shipments declined by 356,000 tons, due to lower demand for cold-rolled
sheets, hot-rolled sheets and galvanised products.
In February the group reached a preliminary agreement on settlement of
along-running pensions liability battle. The deal should eventually pave the
wayfor it to emerge from bankruptcy proceedings.
LTV said yesterday it intended to file a preliminary plan of reorganisation
by May 6. It stressed that negotiations on many key issues would be needed
before its creditors could agree ona package.
</TEXT>
