<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / The Lex Column: Paying the bill for German unity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,498.2 (+26.9)
The G7 wrangle has been billed as a battle between German monetary rectitude
and US profligacy - with virtue winning on points. Judging by the arguments
with which the fiveGerman economic institutes yesterday attacked the case
for higher interest rates, German rectitude is not what it used to be. High
inflation by itself would help slow economic growth, they said, and a
further tightening of monetary policy was therefore unnecessary.
When economists with feebler currencies put such arguments, the German
economic establishment met them with a horse-laugh. No more. With wage
settlements running at 6 to 7 per cent, and likely year-end inflation around
5 per cent, the historic German trade-off between rising prices andeconomic
growth seems to have shifted.
Germany's original partners in the narrow band of the ERM mostly have
relative inflation targets, not absolute ones. The Netherlands perhaps
apart, they are as happy at 4 1/2 per cent inflation as at 3 per cent, so
long as Germany is at 5. The German voter's preference for paying the unity
bill in higher prices rather than higher taxes gives the ERM a dragging
anchor at the expense of higher European inflation and, in time, lower bond
prices.
Part of this is doubtless already in the price; the next movein German bond
yields could even be downwards. But if Germany really is developing a higher
tolerance for inflation, such a drop might not last. UK investors wondering
if convergence with German inflation levels means a long term shift into
bonds and out of equities still have much to ponder.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
