<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Letter: Shades of economic development (2)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PATRICK WILLIAMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In his exposition of a policy for economic development Mr Katz's
inclusion of Hong Kong among countries that exert a degree ofcontrol over
their economies is misleading.
In fact, Hong Kong is an example of a different policy for economic
development. Specifically, the Hong Kong government provides neither
protection from import competition, nor export incentives, tax or other
financial help; nor are key prices adjusted through tax rebates, tariffs,
duties and subsidies.
It is not for us to take sides as to which is the better policy for whatever
circumstances others find themselves in, but our policy has served us
remarkably well.
P. Williamson,
special representative,
Hong Kong and
Economic Trade Office,
Avenue Louise 228,
Brussels
