<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Work changes agreed at Lever Brothers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS ATLever Brothers, the detergents subsidiary of Unilever, have agreed
in principleto changes in working practices after being told that they would
not receive anannual pay rise until they did.
Shop stewards representing 1,750 workers at Lever Brothers' two plants at
Port Sunlight, Merseyside, and Warrington, Cheshire, recommended broad
acceptance of the changes in return for an immediate 8 per cent pay rise
backdated to January.
The broad-ranging changes, known as Horizon 2000, include new shift
patterns, the calculation of working hours over a year, a single pay
structure for blue and white-collar workers, and performance appraisal for
manual workers.
After delays in agreeing the package, the company told workers last month
that they would not backdate any annual pay settlement if it was not
approved by April.
It also indicated that it would consider implementing the measures later
than June.
The company told workers that if there was industrial action it would
withdraw guarantees of no compulsory redundancy and alter early-retirement
policies. It said itneeded changes to combat a serious decline in sales
during the recession. Mr Steve Thomas, chairman of shop stewards at Port
Sunlight, said the stewards recommended acceptance of the offer as the only
sensible option.
The company has offered a 12 per cent rise once details are agreed. A
further 8 per cent will be paid next January, and performance increments -
which it estimates might add another 10 per cent to wages  - in January
1993.
The changes in shift-working arrangements, with a move towards
multi-skilling and more teamworking, are intended to make the measures
self-financing. The company is also offering a new training scheme and
harmonised pay and conditions.
Mr Peter Wright, personnel manager for the plants, said he expected to be
told today that the unions had accepted both the principle of joint
negotiations covering the sites and the main principles of the working
practices changes.
Unions had originally been pressing for a one-year pay deal which would not
be tied to acceptance of Horizon 2000. The company insisted that it would
not pay any rise beforesuch an agreement and would not backdate it if there
were delays.
</TEXT>
