<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Parties play down optimism over
projected gains - Local council elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MAIN political parties are entering the finalstages of the local
election campaigns deliberately playing down forecasts about the number of
seats they will manage to win in Thursday's contest.
Party strategists appear anxious to avoid building expections too high, so
as to leave scope for claiming on Thursday that the results were better than
expected.
Instead, the Labour and Conservative parties are focusing on the main issues
of the campaign, specifically the health service, the new 'council tax' and
the economy.
The government came under further attack yesterday after it indicated that
the seven bands of properties under the new system of local government
taxation could be changed - perhaps to take account of regional variations
in house prices.
Officials insisted, however, that the government's 'strongly preferred
option' was not to increase the number of bands.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, said: 'The dispute over
banding goes straight to the heart of the government's problems. . . The new
tax cannot both be fair and exempt well-off Conservative voters from large
bills.'
The Conservatives hold their final campaign press conference today.
The part y chairman, Mr Chris Patten, and Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, are expected to pin blame for the high level of local
tax bills squarely on high-spending local authorities.
Labour will concentrate on the government's handling of the economy.
The Conservatives are not making public forecasts about Thursday's results,
but privately officials point out that the party is defending a number of
seats it won in 1987, when the party was doing well nationally.
Instead, Tory strategists prefer to make comparisons with last year's local
elections when Labour was regularly far ahead in opinion polls.
They also emphasise how well they believe Labour has to do if it is to have
achance of winning the next general election.
Labour is anxious, however,to distance itself from forecasts at the weekend
that it was poised to gain 600seats. One official said that a gain of
between 250 and 300 seats 'would suit us fine'.
Similarly, for the Liberal Democrats, Mr Archie Kirkwood, campaign manager,
said a 'neutral' result for his party would be a 'cause for celebration'.
'Looked at clinically and against our amazing successes in 1987, I think it
is a very tall order to consider what progress can be made in this
situation,' he said.
'I would not be surprised if we lost seats,' he said.
However, he said his campaigners were confident that this was a pessimistic
scenario. 'In the areas where we have done the work we will get the
rewards,' he said.
</TEXT>
