<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 91 / Parkfield to go into voluntary liquidation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ADMINISTRATION of Parkfield Group, the entertainments and engineering
group that collapsed last year with liabilities of more than Pounds 300m, is
to be ended and the company put into creditors' voluntary liquidation.
In the High Court yesterday the administrators - three partners in Cork
Gully - applied to discharge the administration order, made by the court
last July.
Their counsel, Mr Robin Dicker, said they would be putting Pounds 2.64m  -
the maximum claimed by outstanding preferential creditors of the company -
into a trust account. Any balance left would be remitted to the company.
A resolution for winding-up would be put to a members' meeting next Tuesday.
It was envisaged that the administrators would become the company's
liquidators, Mr Dicker said.
Deputy judge John Weeks, QC, said that discharge of the administration order
would be conditional upon the winding-up resolution being passed. The
administrators would be released 21 days after they had filed their final
accounts, on condition that there was no objection from any creditor or
third party before then.
After yesterday's hearing, the administrators' lawyers said the purpose of
the administration, a more advantageous realisation of Parkfield's assets
thanwould have been possible in a compulsory liquidation, had been achieved.
Most of the parts of the business capable of being sold had been sold and
most of the assets realised. The sooner a liquidation began, the sooner
there could be a distribution to creditors.
</TEXT>
