<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 91 / Dispute may delay Taurus project: City and government
disagree over who should regulate stock market settlement system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DISPUTE has broken out between the City and the government over who should
regulate Taurus, the automated system which will handle the settlement of
stock market transactions.
The disagreement is threatening further delays to the project, which has
already been deferred from October until next Spring.
The latest dispute centres on whether the Department of Trade and Industry
should oversee the system, or whether it should delegate the job to the
Securities and Investments Board and the self-regulating organisations
(SROs) set up under the Financial Services Act.
Oversight of the many brokers, company registrars, custodians and
institutional investors who 'plug in' to the Taurus system, to protect
investors from fraud and other losses, will be one of the biggest and most
important regulatory jobs in the City.
Mr John Redwood, minister for corporate affairs, is thought to fear that
giving the job to SIB and the SROs would lead to an unwarranted increase in
the bureaucracy which has already built up around the Financial Services
Act.
It would bring company registrars (which maintain share registers on behalf
of companies) and custodians (which maintain shareholdings for institutional
investors) within the remit of the FSA regulators for the first time.
Cutting out the SIB, on the other hand, would mean giving more regulatory
power to London's International Stock Exchange, which is to build and run
Taurus. This would be a significant development for the Exchange, which had
its regulatory functions emasculated by the FSA.
Mr Richard Britton, SIB international director, said: 'The SIB doesn't want
to push itself forward and get into empire building. It's up to the
government to decide. We stand ready, if the DTI decides there is a role for
SIB to play.'
Privately, other City regulators express concern that investors could suffer
if SIB and the SROs were not given the job. With the increasing automation
of share trading and settlement, these two processes are becoming difficult
to separate.
Also, they argue that the running of settlement arrangements should fall
within the scope of investor protection legislation. The FSA regulators say
that they receive many complaints about company registrars, but are unable
to deal with them because they are an issue only between companies and their
shareholders.
Cutting out the SIB would also create extra complexity for brokers, since it
would force them to report to a new regulator for Taurus purposes.
A second dispute has arisen over the creation of a new compensation fund to
cover losses through Taurus. The Stock Exchange, with the encouragement of
the DTI, has suggested cover of up to Pounds 250,000 for private investors.
But the SIB, which oversees a scheme with maximum cover of only Pounds
48,000, is concerned about potential overlap between the two arrangements.
The DTI had been hoping to publish its 150-page regulations for Taurus by
the end April. Because no decision has yet been taken on who should oversee
the system, the regulations are now planned towards the end of May.
At the end of last week, the Stock Exchange hinted at further delays in the
eventual introduction of the system when it said that Taurus, the City's
most important single infrastructure development, will be launched 'in the
first half' of 1992.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
