<TEXT>
THE number of staff to be shed at the Rolls-Royce aero-engine plant in
Bristol has been increased by 200, and may reach 1,000, it was announced
yesterday.
Union officials have been warned of possible compulsory redundancies in the
company's 8,000-strong workforce if the job cuts are not met through
voluntary redundancies and early retirement.
The unions have blamed the lack of volunteers on poor pay-offs - the maximum
being Pounds 4,000. Rolls-Royce blamed the company's 3,000 job losses in the
UK on the recession worldwide and the effect of the Gulf war on
international air-lines.
In January the company announced job cuts of between 1,200 and 1,500 jobs at
its Derby commercial aero-engine operations. Derby, where most of
Rolls-Royce's commercial engine business is based, employs about 15,000
people.
