<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Share schemes found not to alter
attitudes of workforce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INTRODUCTION of an employee share ownership scheme in a Midlands factory
had virtually no effect on the attitudes of workers to their employer in its
first year of operation, according to a report, writes Michael Smith.
The study - by Stephen Dunn and Ray Richardson of the London School of
Economics, and Philip Dewe of Massey University - is the latest in a series
of papers debating the worth of companies' providing shares for their
workers at less than the market rate. Some have concluded that companies
with share schemes reap a reward through improved performance; others found
it has no discernible effect.
The report on the unnamed Midlands factory found that there had been no
change in attitudes that could be attributed to the scheme. In some
respects, attitudes towards the employer had deteriorated, although a
dispute over a wage rise may have been largely to blame.
Far fewer employees actually joined the scheme than a survey of initial
interest had indicated. Of 210 employees, 26 had joined the scheme, 57
initially tempted had stayed out and 127 never considered joining.
Among the first and last groups, attitudes toward the employer were broadly
the same in the two surveys. However, among the group that rejected the
scheme after first being tempted, there was more hostility towards the
employer.
'In the event, we concluded that there had been no change in attitudes which
we felt should be attributed to the scheme. If this is correct, it is hard
to see how it could have had any effect on the behaviour of the employees
and any significant advantages to the company,' the report says.
The paper, published in Human Resource Management Journal, says the low
take-up of the scheme indicates its limitations and highlights the dangers.
The authors say membership often becomes the preserve of the relatively
higher-paid, because workers on low incomes are unwilling to make the five
or seven-year commitment necessary to take part fully. The AEU engineering
union has awarded its 159 national officials a pay rise of 10 per cent. The
salaries of Mr Gavin Laird, general secretary, and Mr Bill Jordan,
president, will rise to Pounds 30,250.
The Impact of Employee Share Ownership on Worker Attitudes. Human Resource
Management Journal. Available quarterly by subscription from Industrial
Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
</TEXT>
