<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 91 / G7 agrees need to lower rates: Germany defends economic
policies against pressure from US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MEDIUM-TERM strategy to lower real interest rates and promote world growth
was agreed yesterday by finance ministers and central bank governors from
the Group of Seven main industrial countries.
There was no indication in a communique issued after the meeting in
Washington that Germany had bowed to US pressure for an early cut in its own
interest rates.
Instead, the statement papered over the cracks between the US and Germany,
allowing all sides to claim that a day of tough talks had ended with G7
backing for their respective policies.
The statement emphasised 'the importance of monetary and fiscal policies
which provide the basis for lower real interest rates and a sustained global
economic recovery with price stability'.
Referring to the ministers, it added: 'They believed that such a medium-term
strategy was the best way of reducing potential risks and uncertainties in
the current outlook.'
Mr Nicholas Brady, the US treasury secretary, said the emphasis now was more
on the interdependence of the global economy. This marked a change away from
past communiques which focused on high inflation and slow growth.
He told journalists he believed there was now 'relative price stability in
the US', and he expected that 'over time' there would be lower interest
rates in Germany and Japan.
Mr Karl Otto Pohl, the Bundesbank president, said Germany was not opposed to
lower interest rates, but they had to be earned. The German economy was
expanding strongly and had to react to that. This was now better understood
by the US.
'Policy co-ordination does not mean that countries have to do the same thing
at the same time,' he said. A British official said the statement was in
line with UK policy of promoting growth through price stability. He
emphasised that the communique stressed the importance of fiscal policy in
achieving this end.
Immediately before the G7 met, President George Bush told the finance
ministers and central bank governors from the US, Japan, Germany, France,
Britain, Italy and Canada that the US wanted lower rates to foster global
growth.
The president's unusual intervention demonstrated that US concern about the
risk of worldwide recession exists at the highest political level.
The G7 meeting also discussed the gathering economic crisis in the Soviet
Union, problems of Third World debt and underlined importance of bringing
the Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks to a successful conclusion.
Apart from underlining the need for sustained economic reform in the Soviet
Union, the communique gave no indication of what the west would do.
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, said it was clear there would
be great concern among the G7 if the Soviet Union got into greater
difficulties. Its problems had to be seen in connection with the efforts of
eastern and central Europe to reform their economies and political systems.
He said the G7 would foster dialogue and help for the Soviet Union, showing
the USSR how to boost exports and productivity.
Before the meeting with President Bush, the German and US delegations met
bilaterally to air their differences over the US demand for lower German
interest rates.
Speaking afterwards, both Mr Waigel and Mr Pohl made clear that the German
delegation had delivered a robust defence of German economic and monetary
policies, including the present level of the country's interest rates.
Communique Page 2
British debts plan Page 2
Economics Notebook Page 19
